WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:20.880
Towards the end of the 13th century,
around the year 1293, the Venetian

00:00:20.880 --> 00:00:27.359
explorer and adventurer Marco Polo was
traveling through Southeast Asia in the

00:00:27.359 --> 00:00:34.800
region of what is today Myanmar or Burma.
Marco Polo had spent much of the last 20

00:00:34.800 --> 00:00:39.540
years traveling around the Asian
continent in a remarkable series of

00:00:39.540 --> 00:00:44.579
journeys along the ancient route known
as the Silk Road, and recently he had

00:00:44.579 --> 00:00:51.840
come into the employment of the Mongol
emperor of China, a man named Kublai Khan.

00:00:51.840 --> 00:00:57.300
Impressed by this foreign visitor, the
emperor had appointed Marco Polo an

00:00:57.300 --> 00:01:01.739
ambassador, and he was now traveling
through the forested mountains of

00:01:01.739 --> 00:01:06.900
southwestern China that now stand on the
border of Myanmar.

00:01:06.900 --> 00:01:12.240
He passed through these jungle hills,
thick with bamboo forests and shaded

00:01:12.240 --> 00:01:18.979
groves, and then down into a wide river
valley full of wild animals.

00:01:18.979 --> 00:01:25.680
Leaving the province of Kardandan,
you enter a vast descent which you

00:01:25.680 --> 00:01:31.080
travel without variation for two days
and a half, in the course of which no

00:01:31.080 --> 00:01:37.500
habitations are to be found. You then
reach a spacious plain. Beyond this, in a

00:01:37.500 --> 00:01:44.159
southerly direction, towards the confines
of India, lies the city of Mien.

00:01:44.159 --> 00:01:50.759
The journey occupies 15 days through a
country much depopulated and forests

00:01:50.759 --> 00:01:55.799
abounding with elephants, rhinoceroses,
and other wild beasts,

00:01:55.799 --> 00:01:59.460
where there is not the appearance of any
habitation.

00:01:59.460 --> 00:02:04.680
In this country were found many
elephants, large and handsome wild oxen,

00:02:04.680 --> 00:02:10.679
with stags, fallow deer, and other animals
in great abundance.

00:02:10.679 --> 00:02:17.459
But finally, after more than two weeks,
Marco Polo came across a large city, and

00:02:17.459 --> 00:02:22.560
it was a city that despite all he'd seen
on his travels still stood out to him

00:02:22.560 --> 00:02:29.220
for its size and magnificence, a city
where more than 4,000 golden temples

00:02:29.220 --> 00:02:35.640
sent their spires lancing up into the
afternoon air over the flat pan of the

00:02:35.640 --> 00:02:40.920
river valley.
After the journey of 15 days that has

00:02:40.920 --> 00:02:47.280
been mentioned, you reach the city of
Mien, which is large, magnificent, and the

00:02:47.280 --> 00:02:52.860
capital of the kingdom.
The inhabitants are idolaters and have a

00:02:52.860 --> 00:02:57.840
language peculiar to themselves.
It is related that there formally

00:02:57.840 --> 00:03:03.680
reigned in this country a rich and
powerful monarch.

00:03:03.959 --> 00:03:10.319
The city that Marco Polo called Mien
had fallen on hard times. Everywhere,

00:03:10.319 --> 00:03:16.560
homes were abandoned and temples had
fallen into disuse and disrepair. There

00:03:16.560 --> 00:03:21.959
would have been the signs of war, hungry
and displaced people on the streets, but

00:03:21.959 --> 00:03:27.659
over these sorry sights, the golden
shrines of the city towered and attested

00:03:27.659 --> 00:03:34.200
to its former magnificence. Of all of
these, two enormous temples stood out in

00:03:34.200 --> 00:03:39.659
particular.
When his death was drawing near, the king

00:03:39.659 --> 00:03:45.120
gave orders for erecting on the place of
his internment, at the head and foot of

00:03:45.120 --> 00:03:51.659
the sepulcher, two pyramidal towers
entirely of marble, ten paces in height,

00:03:51.659 --> 00:03:57.799
of a proportionate bulk, and each
terminating with a ball.

00:03:57.799 --> 00:04:04.440
One of these pyramids was covered with a
plate of gold an inch in thickness so

00:04:04.440 --> 00:04:08.879
that nothing besides the gold was
visible, and the other with a plate of

00:04:08.879 --> 00:04:14.220
silver of the same thickness.
Around the balls were suspended small

00:04:14.220 --> 00:04:20.760
bells of gold and of silver, which
sounded when put in motion by the wind.

00:04:20.760 --> 00:04:26.479
The whole formed a splendid object.

00:04:26.639 --> 00:04:33.060
Years later he would return to Italy and
fall on the wrong side of a war between

00:04:33.060 --> 00:04:38.940
the city states of Genoa and Venice, and
he would be thrown in prison by the

00:04:38.940 --> 00:04:42.660
Genoese.
He would share his jail cell with a

00:04:42.660 --> 00:04:48.840
writer named Rustichello da Pisa, who was
greatly impressed with Polo's tales of

00:04:48.840 --> 00:04:53.759
his travels.
While waiting in prison for the war to

00:04:53.759 --> 00:05:00.000
end, the pair of them worked to clarify
Polo's memories and write them down in

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:04.740
vivid detail with what many scholars
consider to be a surprisingly high

00:05:04.740 --> 00:05:10.680
degree of accuracy and authenticity.
Together with the writer Rustichello,

00:05:10.680 --> 00:05:16.139
Marco Polo would become the first
outsider to write a description of a

00:05:16.139 --> 00:05:21.840
city at the heart of an empire that
today we know by the name Bagan.

00:05:21.840 --> 00:05:28.199
For centuries it had united the lands of
Myanmar and presided over a boom in art

00:05:28.199 --> 00:05:33.479
and architecture, constructing one of the
most striking collections of religious

00:05:33.479 --> 00:05:39.780
buildings that the world has ever seen.
The empire of Bagan had flourished and

00:05:39.780 --> 00:05:46.919
survived, and then in a flash, its golden
age had ended, its people had left, and

00:05:46.919 --> 00:05:54.780
its grand temples had fallen slowly into
ruin.

00:06:24.020 --> 00:06:28.860
My name's Paul Cooper, and you're
listening to The Fall of Civilizations

00:06:28.860 --> 00:06:32.880
Podcast.
Each episode, I look at a civilization

00:06:32.880 --> 00:06:39.000
of the past that rose to glory and then
collapsed into the ashes of history.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:44.160
I want to ask, what did they have in
common, what led to their fall, and what

00:06:44.160 --> 00:06:49.380
did it feel like to be a person alive at
the time who witnessed the end of their

00:06:49.380 --> 00:06:53.039
world?
In this episode, I want to tell one of

00:06:53.039 --> 00:06:58.319
the most colorful stories of
civilizational survival, the story of the

00:06:58.319 --> 00:07:04.380
Bagan Empire of medieval Myanmar.
I want to show how this kingdom rose up

00:07:04.380 --> 00:07:09.300
in the Irrawaddy river valley of central
Myanmar, and built one of the most

00:07:09.300 --> 00:07:15.120
remarkable series of monuments to have
survived anywhere in the world. I want to

00:07:15.120 --> 00:07:19.919
show what life was like for the people
who lived there, and what happened to

00:07:19.919 --> 00:07:24.440
cause its sudden and complete collapse.

00:07:31.380 --> 00:07:37.020
The modern country of Myanmar is today
the largest nation by continuous landmass

00:07:37.020 --> 00:07:43.319
in Southeast Asia. It's the size of
Texas and nearly three times larger than

00:07:43.319 --> 00:07:48.599
the United Kingdom.
Myanmar borders India in the west and

00:07:48.599 --> 00:07:54.060
China in the east, and its lands stretch
between the mountain ranges the Arakan,

00:07:54.060 --> 00:08:00.479
the Pegu, the Chin, and the Shan Yoma.
Between the bony peaks of these mountain

00:08:00.479 --> 00:08:05.759
ranges that run like a series of spines
north to south down the whole country,

00:08:05.759 --> 00:08:11.099
flow the rivers Chindwin, Shweli, N’mai,
and Mali.

00:08:11.099 --> 00:08:16.440
Many of these rivers begin in the
Himalayan glaciers of upper Burma, and

00:08:16.440 --> 00:08:21.539
all of them flow down through the gorges
of the high mountains and join the

00:08:21.539 --> 00:08:25.919
largest watercourse of all in a wide and
sinuous flow.

00:08:25.919 --> 00:08:33.360
This is the great river Irrawaddy.
The name of the Irrawaddy River derives

00:08:33.360 --> 00:08:39.120
from the Sanskrit name Airavati, a
legendary white elephant with four tusks

00:08:39.120 --> 00:08:44.399
and the seven trunks, who in Hindu
mythology is the trusted mount of the

00:08:44.399 --> 00:08:49.560
god Indra, and it's not hard to see why
the river deserves this grand and

00:08:49.560 --> 00:08:53.880
mythical name.
The Irrawaddy River winds for more than

00:08:53.880 --> 00:08:59.580
two thousand kilometers across the Dry
Zone of Burma, through palm forests and

00:08:59.580 --> 00:09:05.640
scrublands, and around sandy islands.
The river is also one of Asia's widest,

00:09:05.640 --> 00:09:11.100
and at points during the rainy season, it
can swell to nearly a kilometer across.

00:09:11.100 --> 00:09:16.140
These floods can be so dramatic that for
millennia, the people of Burma have built

00:09:16.140 --> 00:09:21.000
houses along the river on top of tall
bamboo stilts that allow the flood

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:25.560
waters to rise below them.
At the end of the river's journey, the

00:09:25.560 --> 00:09:31.019
Irrawaddy branches out into a wide delta
of mangrove forests, marshes, and

00:09:31.019 --> 00:09:37.459
meandering streams, where it finally
empties into the Southern Ocean.

00:09:37.680 --> 00:09:42.899
The general center of the river's course
is an arid heartland that's known as

00:09:42.899 --> 00:09:47.459
Myanmar's Dry Zone, since it receives a
relatively small amount of rainfall

00:09:47.459 --> 00:09:51.600
every year.
The mountains that surround this wide

00:09:51.600 --> 00:09:57.600
basin on three sides soak up much of the
moisture, holding back the clouds like a

00:09:57.600 --> 00:10:01.500
great wall.
But the rain falls instead in the hills,

00:10:01.500 --> 00:10:06.600
and this rainwater then flows down
through the great river Irrawaddy.

00:10:06.600 --> 00:10:10.800
This means that so long as you stay
close to the river, the Dry Zone is

00:10:10.800 --> 00:10:17.220
actually never short of water.
Since humans first arrived in Myanmar,

00:10:17.220 --> 00:10:22.740
people have flocked to the banks of this
river to make their livelihoods, to farm

00:10:22.740 --> 00:10:27.560
their rice, and to build their towns.

00:10:34.080 --> 00:10:41.279
The earliest cultures we have evidence
for arrived in Myanmar around 11,000 BC,

00:10:41.279 --> 00:10:47.100
and by about 1500 BC, people in the
region were already turning copper into

00:10:47.100 --> 00:10:52.500
bronze, growing rice, and domesticating
chickens and pigs, and they would be

00:10:52.500 --> 00:10:57.480
among the first people in the world to
farm these animals for food.

00:10:57.480 --> 00:11:04.760
By around 500 BC, iron was being worked
in the region.

00:11:05.519 --> 00:11:10.440
Since the earliest history, the rivers have
also been highways.

00:11:10.440 --> 00:11:16.260
The people of Myanmar have always built
watercraft, often rafts made out of the

00:11:16.260 --> 00:11:21.779
strong and light Burmese bamboo that
grows everywhere along stream banks and

00:11:21.779 --> 00:11:27.660
in the lower hills, or more refined
barges made of teakwood.

00:11:27.660 --> 00:11:34.140
The teak tree has adapted to contain a
large amount of natural oil, giving it an

00:11:34.140 --> 00:11:39.779
exceptional water resistance.
The teak growing in Burma is so abundant

00:11:39.779 --> 00:11:44.940
that it has been used to make enormous
constructions like bridges that have

00:11:44.940 --> 00:11:50.180
lasted for nearly 200 years.
One famous bridge named U Bein

00:11:50.180 --> 00:11:55.920
spans more than a kilometer across
Taungthaman Lake, and is made up of more than a

00:11:55.920 --> 00:12:00.000
thousand teakwood pillars driven into
the lake bed.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:05.640
The people here even build floating
island gardens that rise and fall with

00:12:05.640 --> 00:12:09.959
the water level, and which for centuries
have turned the surface of the lake

00:12:09.959 --> 00:12:16.200
into productive agricultural land.
If people wanted to travel south, they

00:12:16.200 --> 00:12:21.180
could easily float their boats
downstream, but the prevailing winds also

00:12:21.180 --> 00:12:26.220
blew south to north, meaning that it was
also possible to sail against the

00:12:26.220 --> 00:12:31.800
current, making travel in both directions
along the river relatively easy.

00:12:31.800 --> 00:12:36.779
The Irrawaddy River was so conceptually
important to the history of this region

00:12:36.779 --> 00:12:41.700
that people in Burma would rarely talk
about the country in terms of north and

00:12:41.700 --> 00:12:49.920
south, but rather used the words anya and
akye, upstream and downstream.

00:12:49.920 --> 00:12:56.100
One traditional Burmese poet describes
the coming of summer in the landscape of

00:12:56.100 --> 00:12:59.120
the Irrawaddy valley.

00:13:05.300 --> 00:13:11.519
As the hot season revolts against the
cold in the pattern of contrasts, the sky

00:13:11.519 --> 00:13:17.579
becomes cloudy and winds are hot again.
It is summer.  The leaves on trees turn yellow

00:13:17.579 --> 00:13:23.639
to fall to show new leaves.
Stems twist or break, yet sprouts on tama

00:13:23.639 --> 00:13:28.740
trees are now soft greens like parrot
eggs, while in summer trees thirst in

00:13:28.740 --> 00:13:34.440
foothills, tazin flowers are climbing
tabye trees, effusing fragrance, mixing

00:13:34.440 --> 00:13:39.959
with the wafting air.  At sunset, crow
pheasants are cooing, and from afar come

00:13:39.959 --> 00:13:44.760
the cuckoo's notes. Now and again, thunder
is beating through Heaven's expanses

00:13:44.760 --> 00:13:51.240
like lambara anddeindi drums, and I, oh,
I think of the pouring of water on the

00:13:51.240 --> 00:13:56.519
Bodhi tree and of the absent companion
in the Golden Palace of Victory,

00:13:56.519 --> 00:14:00.920
and I am mournful.

00:14:08.339 --> 00:14:13.200
Like many languages in Southeast Asia,
the Burmese language has different

00:14:13.200 --> 00:14:18.720
levels of register depending on how
polite or formal you need to be, and the

00:14:18.720 --> 00:14:22.820
land itself has different names
depending on the register you're using.

00:14:22.820 --> 00:14:28.920
In everyday speech, people most commonly
use the name Bama to describe the

00:14:28.920 --> 00:14:34.800
country and its people, while the grander
and more poetic name is Myanmar.

00:14:34.800 --> 00:14:40.320
Both of these names have been used
alongside each other for centuries.

00:14:40.320 --> 00:14:45.480
When the country became a British colony,
the colonial government used the

00:14:45.480 --> 00:14:50.339
informal name Burma, which is the name
that British people first heard being

00:14:50.339 --> 00:14:56.699
used by common sailors and traders.
But in 1989, the military dictatorship

00:14:56.699 --> 00:15:01.740
that then ruled the country changed the
name officially to the grander name of

00:15:01.740 --> 00:15:05.579
Myanmar.
Because of this complicated history, in

00:15:05.579 --> 00:15:09.360
Myanmar today, the question of the
country's name has deep-rooted

00:15:09.360 --> 00:15:14.639
controversies, but in this episode I will
follow the example of the majority of

00:15:14.639 --> 00:15:24.380
Burmese people and use both names
interchangeably depending on context.

00:15:25.800 --> 00:15:31.500
So, it's on this geographical stage
that the story of the Bagan Empire would

00:15:31.500 --> 00:15:37.680
play out, in the Dry Zone of the country,
surrounded on all sides by mountains and

00:15:37.680 --> 00:15:42.000
watered by the great river highway, the
Irrawaddy.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:45.899
For much of this region's history,
whoever controlled the Dry Zone

00:15:45.899 --> 00:15:51.480
controlled the rest of the country, and
so, it was also a land soaked in the

00:15:51.480 --> 00:15:55.579
blood of conflict.

00:15:58.320 --> 00:16:04.260
There were two major sources for events
in Myanmar during the medieval period.

00:16:04.260 --> 00:16:09.720
The first of these are the inscriptions
left carved in stone at many temples and

00:16:09.720 --> 00:16:15.000
other buildings, which kings left in
order to celebrate their deeds, and the

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:20.160
second of these sources is the so-called
Chronicles of Burma.

00:16:20.160 --> 00:16:24.540
These chronicles are a diverse
collection of documents written over

00:16:24.540 --> 00:16:30.360
many centuries by monks and scholars on
different materials. Some are written on

00:16:30.360 --> 00:16:36.540
paper made of the Siamese rough bush
tree or paper mulberry, glued into very

00:16:36.540 --> 00:16:41.820
long sheets and folded in a concertina
fashion, while others are written on palm

00:16:41.820 --> 00:16:47.759
leaf or even carved into stone tablets.
The first chronicle that has survived

00:16:47.759 --> 00:16:52.860
was written in the 13th century during
the Bagan era.

00:16:52.860 --> 00:16:57.720
The so-called Maha Yazawin, or Great
Chronicle, was completed several

00:16:57.720 --> 00:17:03.720
centuries later in the year 1724, and it
was followed nearly a century later by

00:17:03.720 --> 00:17:08.220
the Yazawin Thit, or New Chronicle, which
attempted to square some of the

00:17:08.220 --> 00:17:12.720
contradictions between the chronicles
and the stone inscriptions, as its author

00:17:12.720 --> 00:17:18.419
writes in his introduction.
There are chronicles written by ancient

00:17:18.419 --> 00:17:23.280
scholars, but in those chronicles written
by ancient scholars, there are some

00:17:23.280 --> 00:17:27.900
matters which do not accord with the
inscriptions.

00:17:27.900 --> 00:17:33.419
Like many such historical documents,
these chronicles were paid for by kings

00:17:33.419 --> 00:17:38.220
and produced under their supervision, and
they are instruments of official

00:17:38.220 --> 00:17:43.500
propaganda.  They are also full of
exaggeration, poetic license, and

00:17:43.500 --> 00:17:48.960
mythology, especially in the earlier
reaches of Burmese history. They include

00:17:48.960 --> 00:17:54.480
truly ludicrous exaggerations about the
size of armies, often describing battles

00:17:54.480 --> 00:17:59.340
involving tens of millions of soldiers,
and they frequently include the colorful

00:17:59.340 --> 00:18:05.400
appearances of ogres, ghosts, ghouls,
demons, and magicians, along with

00:18:05.400 --> 00:18:10.080
countless figures from Burmese mythology.
But in all their fantastical

00:18:10.080 --> 00:18:15.240
presentation, these chronicles can
combine with official inscriptions to

00:18:15.240 --> 00:18:19.980
preserve relatively accurate dates and
events, and they also preserve the

00:18:19.980 --> 00:18:26.760
folklore and traditional memory of the
people. In the year 1829, the king Bagyidaw

00:18:26.760 --> 00:18:30.840
of Burma appointed a committee of
scholars to write a chronicle of the

00:18:30.840 --> 00:18:35.340
Burmese kings that would act as the
final complete edition.

00:18:35.340 --> 00:18:40.260
He gathered them in the glittering front
wing of his residence, known as the Glass

00:18:40.260 --> 00:18:46.460
Palace, and instructed them to get to
work. The king of the law, seeing the many

00:18:46.460 --> 00:18:51.539
discrepancies and repetitions in the
former chronicles, gave thought to the

00:18:51.539 --> 00:18:56.880
matter. Being convinced that a chronicle
of kings should be the standard and not

00:18:56.880 --> 00:19:01.380
a thing of conflicting and false
statements, he assembled his ministers

00:19:01.380 --> 00:19:06.000
and ecclesiastical teachers in the front
chamber of the palace, which was

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:11.160
variegated with diverse gems and a fit
place for the most exalted personages,

00:19:11.160 --> 00:19:16.440
and caused the chronicle to be purified
by comparing it with other chronicles

00:19:16.440 --> 00:19:21.600
and a number of inscriptions each with
the other, and adopting the truth in the

00:19:21.600 --> 00:19:26.299
light of reason and the traditional
books.

00:19:26.520 --> 00:19:31.980
This document, full of tangents and
footnotes, would become known as the

00:19:31.980 --> 00:19:37.020
Glass Palace Chronicle. Despite its
complicated nature, it's a remarkable

00:19:37.020 --> 00:19:42.600
text that gives us a real glimpse of how
the people of ancient Bagan felt and

00:19:42.600 --> 00:19:48.240
thought about their lives and the world
around them, as well as the birth of

00:19:48.240 --> 00:19:50.720
their empire.

00:19:57.120 --> 00:20:02.580
The origins of the people who first
spoke the Burmese language are wreathed

00:20:02.580 --> 00:20:08.520
in mystery. The Burmese chronicles claim
a line of kings going back to the second

00:20:08.520 --> 00:20:13.260
century, but modern scholars and
archaeologists consider this to be

00:20:13.260 --> 00:20:18.600
extremely unlikely. One more plausible
account traces the history of these

00:20:18.600 --> 00:20:27.120
people back to the early 9th century and
the powerful kingdom named Nanchao.

00:20:27.120 --> 00:20:33.720
The power of Nanchao ruled over the area
across the mountains to the east, in what

00:20:33.720 --> 00:20:39.120
is today the lofty province of Yunnan in
Western China.

00:20:39.120 --> 00:20:44.820
For years, the kings of Nanchao had set
their sights on the rich river valley of

00:20:44.820 --> 00:20:49.320
the Irrawaddy.
The year was 832.

00:20:49.320 --> 00:20:54.419
Around the world at this time, the
Byzantine Empire, the last remaining part

00:20:54.419 --> 00:20:58.860
of what had been the Roman Empire, was
fighting for its life against

00:20:58.860 --> 00:21:05.460
increasingly confident Arab empires
inspired by the young religion of Islam.

00:21:05.460 --> 00:21:11.940
In the Mayan lowlands of southern Mexico,
the last king of the soaring city of

00:21:11.940 --> 00:21:17.580
Copan, a man named Ukit Took, was
commissioning a stone monument that

00:21:17.580 --> 00:21:22.200
would never be finished because his
entire society was collapsing under the

00:21:22.200 --> 00:21:27.419
pressures of drought and warfare, and the
population was fleeing the city.

00:21:27.419 --> 00:21:32.760
In what is today France, King Pepin I
of Aquitaine and his brother Louis

00:21:32.760 --> 00:21:38.580
the German revolted against their father,
the Frankish Emperor Louis the Pious, the

00:21:38.580 --> 00:21:42.179
son of Charlemagne,
and in the mountains of southern China,

00:21:42.179 --> 00:21:48.600
the armies of Nanchao marched out to
conquer the lands of Burma.

00:21:48.600 --> 00:21:54.720
At that time, the society occupying the
Dry Zone around the Irrawaddy was a people

00:21:54.720 --> 00:22:00.600
who are remembered as the Pyu.
Exactly who the Pyu were and what they

00:22:00.600 --> 00:22:05.760
called themselves, we have little idea. It
seems they spoke a language of the

00:22:05.760 --> 00:22:10.140
Sino-Tibetan family and lived in a
loosely-connected group of five

00:22:10.140 --> 00:22:16.380
city states in the valley of the Irrawaddy.
Their culture was heavily influenced by

00:22:16.380 --> 00:22:21.900
trade with India. In the preceding
centuries, they had imported Buddhism as

00:22:21.900 --> 00:22:26.760
well as other Indian cultural concepts,
architectural styles, and political

00:22:26.760 --> 00:22:31.679
structures, and they had based their
writing system on the Indian Brahmi

00:22:31.679 --> 00:22:36.240
script.
One 9th century Chinese text known as

00:22:36.240 --> 00:22:41.640
the Manchu or the Book of Southern
Barbarians, records the Chinese

00:22:41.640 --> 00:22:47.100
impressions of this land and the Pyu
people who lived there.

00:22:47.100 --> 00:22:53.640
To the south of Yongchang City, one first
passes beyond the lands of the Tang

00:22:53.640 --> 00:23:01.620
Empire to phoenix-blue jungles, then to
vast skies, then to clearings. There lie

00:23:01.620 --> 00:23:07.679
huge rivers and settlements. They live in
multi-storied houses, without city walls,

00:23:07.679 --> 00:23:13.440
sometimes painting their teeth, always
dressing in untreated cloth with rattan

00:23:13.440 --> 00:23:18.659
warn about their waist, red silk cloth
wrapped about their top knot, and other

00:23:18.659 --> 00:23:22.039
hair hanging behind in a decorative
fashion.

00:23:22.039 --> 00:23:27.240
Peacocks nest in nearby trees, and
elephants are as large as water buffalo.

00:23:27.240 --> 00:23:32.700
The locals customarily raise elephants
to till the fields and burn their dung

00:23:32.700 --> 00:23:37.140
as fuel.
The armies of Nanchao marched through the

00:23:37.140 --> 00:23:42.539
narrow mountain passes thickly carpeted
with forest, and swept through the

00:23:42.539 --> 00:23:48.419
Burmese lowlands on a series of
devastating raids, taking both plunder

00:23:48.419 --> 00:23:53.100
and slaves.
In the 10th year of the Zhenyuan era,

00:23:53.100 --> 00:23:58.620
Nanchao sought out and attacked them. On
the 21st day of the 12th month of the

00:23:58.620 --> 00:24:04.200
third year of the Sheeantong era, at the
cliffs of the Suli River, some 2,000 to

00:24:04.200 --> 00:24:09.659
3,000 troops massed.
According to ancient sources, the Nanchao

00:24:09.659 --> 00:24:13.799
deported many thousands of the Pyu
people who lived and farmed in this

00:24:13.799 --> 00:24:18.000
fertile valley and sent them away into
slavery.

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:23.700
Among the troops of Nanchao were a group
of cavalry warriors from a people known

00:24:23.700 --> 00:24:30.000
as the Mien, a small ethnic tribe from
the high plateaus who spoke an ancestor

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:33.240
of what would become the Burmese
language.

00:24:33.240 --> 00:24:37.980
But these troops had dreams of going
their own way, and once they had tasted

00:24:37.980 --> 00:24:44.880
freedom in the valley of the Irrawaddy,
they had no desire to return to Nanchao.

00:24:44.880 --> 00:24:50.520
Used to life in the rocky mountain
plateaus of the north, the arid plains of

00:24:50.520 --> 00:24:55.620
Burma were a familiar ecology to them,
and with the native population there

00:24:55.620 --> 00:25:01.080
devastated by the Nanchao raids, their
lands were there for the taking.

00:25:01.080 --> 00:25:06.539
The Mien broke away from the kingdom of
Nanchao and decided to settle in this

00:25:06.539 --> 00:25:11.039
new land, and ultimately they would found
a kingdom there.

00:25:11.039 --> 00:25:15.720
Other historians contest that the
Burmese speakers already existed in the

00:25:15.720 --> 00:25:20.520
valley and that they were part of the
Pi’ao people and had nothing to do with

00:25:20.520 --> 00:25:24.419
the Nanchao raids.
But as with everything in these early

00:25:24.419 --> 00:25:29.159
stages of the chronicles, we’re left with
a hazy fog of contradictions and

00:25:29.159 --> 00:25:35.159
uncertainties, and the answer actually
may have been a mix of both.

00:25:35.159 --> 00:25:40.020
On the other side of the world at the
same time, seagoing Norsemen from

00:25:40.020 --> 00:25:45.200
Scandinavia were arriving in great
numbers on the shores of Eastern England,

00:25:45.200 --> 00:25:51.659
sometimes as raiders, sometimes as
settlers, and sometimes as refugees, and

00:25:51.659 --> 00:25:55.860
over the next century, they would come to
topple the Saxon kingdoms that ruled

00:25:55.860 --> 00:26:00.659
there, and as they did so, they would plant
a distinctly Norse character on the

00:26:00.659 --> 00:26:05.520
people of England and the English
language that emerged from them.

00:26:05.520 --> 00:26:10.140
I think it's possible that the Burmese
people then settling in the Irrawaddy

00:26:10.140 --> 00:26:15.659
valley may have arrived in similarly
complex circumstances and formed a

00:26:15.659 --> 00:26:20.659
similar hybrid culture with the people
who lived there.

00:26:23.760 --> 00:26:28.679
With much of this matter concealed in
the fog of history, what we can say with

00:26:28.679 --> 00:26:35.039
some certainty is that around the year
849, just 17 years after the date given

00:26:35.039 --> 00:26:40.860
to the Nanchao raids, the Mien built a
walled fortress at a place on the eastern

00:26:40.860 --> 00:26:45.360
bank of the Irrawaddy River,
a place that would later come to be

00:26:45.360 --> 00:26:48.740
known as Bagan.

00:26:50.700 --> 00:26:56.039
The chosen location for the city of
Bagan owed much to the geography of the

00:26:56.039 --> 00:27:01.080
land around it. It seems to have been
built on the ruins of a previous

00:27:01.080 --> 00:27:06.840
settlement belonging to the Pyu people,
and stood on a sizable bend in the

00:27:06.840 --> 00:27:12.120
meandering course of the Irrawaddy River.
The settlement had easy access to water

00:27:12.120 --> 00:27:16.679
and was surrounded by countryside that
would be the most fertile and productive

00:27:16.679 --> 00:27:24.179
of all Myanmar for the next 500 years.
Part of the reason for this was the

00:27:24.179 --> 00:27:30.000
region's violent geological history.
Around 50 kilometers to the southeast of

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:36.600
Bagan was a great dormant volcano named
Mount Popa. This volcanic cone, covered in

00:27:36.600 --> 00:27:42.419
thick forest and shaded bamboo groves, is
a sacred site that for centuries has

00:27:42.419 --> 00:27:47.460
been the focal point of worship for the
people of Burma. Southwest of Mount Popa

00:27:47.460 --> 00:27:54.659
is Taung Kalat or Pedestal Hill, a
striking sheer-sided volcanic plug which

00:27:54.659 --> 00:28:00.480
rises more than 650 meters above sea-
-level, and where a Buddhist monastery now

00:28:00.480 --> 00:28:04.980
sits towering over the forested
landscape below.

00:28:04.980 --> 00:28:10.320
Mount Popa has long been believed to be
the home of powerful spirits that the

00:28:10.320 --> 00:28:15.120
Burmese call Nats, and the worship of
these spirits has always existed

00:28:15.120 --> 00:28:21.299
alongside Buddhist religious practices
in a complex relationship.

00:28:21.299 --> 00:28:26.340
While this soaring mountain rising out
of the flat plain has long captured the

00:28:26.340 --> 00:28:31.020
imaginations and religious sensibilities
of the people, it was also partly to

00:28:31.020 --> 00:28:36.240
thank for the success of their society.
The ash that volcanoes spew out during

00:28:36.240 --> 00:28:42.600
their eruptions is rich in elements such
as iron, magnesium, and potassium, minerals

00:28:42.600 --> 00:28:48.059
that are crucial for the healthy growth
of plants. When volcanic rock and ash

00:28:48.059 --> 00:28:54.120
weather and leach into the soil, these
elements are released. So, combined

00:28:54.120 --> 00:28:59.159
with the fertility of the silty soil
along the river itself and the plentiful

00:28:59.159 --> 00:29:03.840
water supply, this meant that the soils
in this region were immensely productive,

00:29:03.840 --> 00:29:09.419
and the people of Bagan were able to
conduct two bountiful rice harvests per

00:29:09.419 --> 00:29:16.740
year and grow other crops like pulses,
sesamum, cucumbers, and millet.

00:29:16.740 --> 00:29:22.020
On the spot that they'd chosen for their
new city, the Mien built a thick and high

00:29:22.020 --> 00:29:26.159
wall out of brick,
and they built it according to the

00:29:26.159 --> 00:29:31.820
traditions of Buddhist cosmology and
numerology.

00:29:33.360 --> 00:29:38.700
The inner wall of Bagan was broken by
twelve gates to represent the twelve

00:29:38.700 --> 00:29:44.460
signs of the Zodiac, with four main gates
at each of the cardinal directions; north,

00:29:44.460 --> 00:29:49.679
south, east, and west.
The walled area of the city wasn't huge,

00:29:49.679 --> 00:29:55.200
a little over a square kilometer in fact,
but the walls contained only the palaces

00:29:55.200 --> 00:30:00.419
of the kings and the headquarters of his
administration. Outside this fortified

00:30:00.419 --> 00:30:05.880
center, a sprawling city would soon grow
up around it, much of it built out of

00:30:05.880 --> 00:30:11.299
teak and bamboo that has left little
trace in the archaeological record.

00:30:11.299 --> 00:30:17.279
By the mid 10th century, a king was in
place in Bagan, although we don't know

00:30:17.279 --> 00:30:23.220
the exact names and dates for these
early kings. One 9th century Arab

00:30:23.220 --> 00:30:28.440
traveler to India and Burma, named
Sulayman Nadwi, wrote an account of the

00:30:28.440 --> 00:30:33.020
powerful army that one king of Burma
fielded.

00:30:33.020 --> 00:30:38.580
They said that when he marches to battle,
he is accompanied by about 50,000

00:30:38.580 --> 00:30:44.340
elephants. He campaigns only in winter.
Indeed, his elephants cannot stand thirst,

00:30:44.340 --> 00:30:49.980
and so they can go forth only in winter.
They say that in his army, even the

00:30:49.980 --> 00:30:55.460
washermen amounted between 10 and
15,000.

00:30:55.620 --> 00:31:00.179
Thanks to the ongoing study of
inscriptions, we do know the names of at

00:31:00.179 --> 00:31:05.360
least two kings who ruled around the
turn of the first millennium; Nyaung-u Sawrahan

00:31:05.360 --> 00:31:12.080
and Kyaung Pjy Min, both of whom were once
considered to be legendary. By the year

00:31:12.080 --> 00:31:17.820
1004, a Chinese source from the Song
Dynasty records an ambassador arriving

00:31:17.820 --> 00:31:22.620
from what they called the P’u-kan
kingdom, which is thought to refer to

00:31:22.620 --> 00:31:28.140
Bagan. It seems this ambassador was
seeking recognition from Song China,

00:31:28.140 --> 00:31:32.820
which was then considered the great
power in the region, suggesting that the

00:31:32.820 --> 00:31:37.380
kingdom of Bagan was now confident
enough to look outwards and assert

00:31:37.380 --> 00:31:41.700
itself to its neighbors.
But reliable sources on these early

00:31:41.700 --> 00:31:46.500
kings are extremely thin and all mixed
up with legend.

00:31:46.500 --> 00:31:51.539
The first king of Bagan who steps out of
the historical record in full color

00:31:51.539 --> 00:31:56.760
would not come for another half-century.
He was long considered the founder of

00:31:56.760 --> 00:32:01.320
the Bagan Empire, and although we now
know that it was likely in existence for

00:32:01.320 --> 00:32:07.140
two centuries or so before his reign, he
is arguably its first great king, and

00:32:07.140 --> 00:32:11.399
certainly the king who would lead it to
new and glorious heights.

00:32:11.399 --> 00:32:16.039
He was a man named Anawrahta.

00:32:23.120 --> 00:32:28.559
Anawrahta's early life was one of
upheaval and family conflict.

00:32:28.559 --> 00:32:34.080
His father was the king, but he had been
a usurper on the throne of Bagan, having

00:32:34.080 --> 00:32:39.720
overthrown the previous king in a
rebellion, and like most usurpers,

00:32:39.720 --> 00:32:46.399
Anawrahta’s father lived in constant fear of
one day being overthrown himself.

00:32:46.399 --> 00:32:51.679
Anawrahta grew up as a prince in the
palace with his two older step-brothers,

00:32:51.679 --> 00:32:58.380
men named Kyizo and Sokkate.
These brothers were actually the sons of

00:32:58.380 --> 00:33:04.020
the previous king, but Anawrahta's father
had adopted them and raised them as his

00:33:04.020 --> 00:33:10.020
own, and so they grew up together.
But his older stepbrothers Kyizo and

00:33:10.020 --> 00:33:15.720
Sokkate always treated the younger
Anawrahta as though he were an inferior,

00:33:15.720 --> 00:33:19.559
something that must have rankled the
young prince.

00:33:19.559 --> 00:33:24.899
It's clear that these two brothers
also dreamed of one day reclaiming some

00:33:24.899 --> 00:33:30.860
of the glory that their adoptive father
had stolen from them.

00:33:35.820 --> 00:33:41.820
While he was still a boy, Anawrahta's
treacherous brothers plotted a coup to

00:33:41.820 --> 00:33:49.340
overthrow his now aging father, as the
Glass Palace Chronicle recalls.

00:33:49.679 --> 00:33:56.460
When Kyizo and Sokkate came of age, they
built a pleasant monastery and said to

00:33:56.460 --> 00:34:01.559
King Kunhsaw, ‘Come and call thy blessings
on the monastery,’

00:34:01.559 --> 00:34:08.460
and the king took no heed nor scrutiny,
but hearkened to them, and Kyizo and

00:34:08.460 --> 00:34:14.760
Sokkate seized the king and threatened him
and made him become a monk, and they

00:34:14.760 --> 00:34:21.300
spread the rumor far and wide that the
king, in his zeal for bliss hereafter, had

00:34:21.300 --> 00:34:24.139
become a monk.

00:34:24.359 --> 00:34:30.119
This palace coup must have scandalized
the Royal Court, and despite the relative

00:34:30.119 --> 00:34:35.460
commonness of coups of this kind, the
historians of Burma are clear in their

00:34:35.460 --> 00:34:40.679
view on it. The Glass Palace Chronicle
recounts how a number of evil omens

00:34:40.679 --> 00:34:46.980
accompanied this shocking act.
About the time of his fall, a miracle was

00:34:46.980 --> 00:34:52.980
seen in the Pahto pagoda. The Friday star
trampled on the moon. The moon was a full

00:34:52.980 --> 00:34:58.560
circle on the second day of waxing. The
Earth quaked seven days. The water stood

00:34:58.560 --> 00:35:01.520
still in the river.

00:35:02.040 --> 00:35:07.800
First, the brother named Kyizo ruled as
king, but the chronicles recall that he

00:35:07.800 --> 00:35:13.440
was killed one day by a hunter who
mistook him for a deer.

00:35:13.440 --> 00:35:19.260
He built a royal box in the marshes of
the Chindwin and visited the ten

00:35:19.260 --> 00:35:26.400
villages of Bangyi, hunting deer. One day, a
hunter lay waiting for thamine at the

00:35:26.400 --> 00:35:31.079
place where they drank water.
The king likewise came to the spot to

00:35:31.079 --> 00:35:37.079
wait for deer, and the hunter knew not
that it was the king, but shot with the

00:35:37.079 --> 00:35:44.579
bow and hit him that he died. He passed
at the age of 28. About the time of his

00:35:44.579 --> 00:35:53.300
death, an ogre laughed for a full half
month and threw stones at the palace.

00:35:55.260 --> 00:36:00.420
After this unfortunate accident, the
other treacherous brother Sokkate took

00:36:00.420 --> 00:36:04.619
the throne, and it's perhaps not
unreasonable to wonder whether this

00:36:04.619 --> 00:36:09.420
story of the hunter accidentally killing
the king might actually be a polite way

00:36:09.420 --> 00:36:14.160
for the chroniclers to get around the
fact that the new king had actually had

00:36:14.160 --> 00:36:19.740
his brother Kyizo assassinated.
Through all of this upheaval and

00:36:19.740 --> 00:36:25.500
treachery, the boy Anawrahta seems to have
simply got on with things. He was allowed

00:36:25.500 --> 00:36:30.420
to keep his royal status at court and to
live there with his mother, and in

00:36:30.420 --> 00:36:35.880
exchange he attended to the two kings
who had overthrown his father and taken

00:36:35.880 --> 00:36:41.400
away the throne that would one day have
been his. But when Anawrahta had reached

00:36:41.400 --> 00:36:47.359
the age of 30, King Sokkate took things
too far.

00:36:47.700 --> 00:36:54.359
He referred to Anawrahta at court using
the word Nyitha-naungme, a compound word

00:36:54.359 --> 00:37:00.540
that means something like brother-son.
Confused by this, Anawrahta traveled to

00:37:00.540 --> 00:37:06.420
the monastery where his father had been
exiled and asked him what it meant.

00:37:06.420 --> 00:37:11.280
To the old embittered former king, the
meaning of this was clear;

00:37:11.280 --> 00:37:16.760
Sokkate intended to marry Anawrahta's
mother.

00:37:16.760 --> 00:37:23.480
Anawrahta told that word to his father
King Kyaungbyu, and his father said,

00:37:23.480 --> 00:37:29.720
‘Because he wishes to take thy mother,
thus he speaks.’  Anawrahta

00:37:29.720 --> 00:37:36.480
was exceedingly angry and he begged for
the horse and weapons and gear that

00:37:36.480 --> 00:37:41.280
Sakra gave his father,
and his father gave him the Areindama

00:37:41.280 --> 00:37:49.079
lance, the Thilawuntha sword, the ruby ring,
and the ruby hairpin.

00:37:49.079 --> 00:37:54.300
It's hard to know whether Anawrahta was
truly motivated by his mother's honor or

00:37:54.300 --> 00:37:58.680
whether he had been planning this the
whole time and had just now found a

00:37:58.680 --> 00:38:04.020
convenient excuse.
Whatever the case, Anawrahta rose in

00:38:04.020 --> 00:38:09.839
rebellion against his stepbrother.
He fled to the holy volcano, Mount Popa,

00:38:09.839 --> 00:38:15.540
and marshaled his forces there, gathering
lords and chieftains who had had enough

00:38:15.540 --> 00:38:22.619
of the brothers treacherous antics. Then
he marched on the capital of Bagan.

00:38:22.619 --> 00:38:28.320
The Glass Palace Chronicle records what
happened next.

00:38:28.320 --> 00:38:35.220
Now, when he had mustered his forces, he
marched on Bagan and sent a message to

00:38:35.220 --> 00:38:41.160
his brother saying, will you give up the
throne or will you do battle? And when

00:38:41.160 --> 00:38:46.320
Sokkate heard the words of his younger
brother, he was exceedingly wrathful and

00:38:46.320 --> 00:38:51.720
answered, his mother's milk is yet wet
upon his lips, and he says he will fight

00:38:51.720 --> 00:38:59.599
me? Let all my ministers look on. I will
fight him man to man, on horseback. When

00:38:59.599 --> 00:39:06.060
Anawrahta heard his brother's words, he was
glad, and when the appointed day was come,

00:39:06.060 --> 00:39:12.060
he took the lance and sword his father
had given him and mounted the demon

00:39:12.060 --> 00:39:18.660
horse and came to the stream of Tamati,
and Sokkate, his brother, saw him coming

00:39:18.660 --> 00:39:26.400
and went forth to meet him. Then said,
‘Anawrahta, brother, you the elder strike

00:39:26.400 --> 00:39:30.839
first,’ and
Sokkate thrust at him with his lance,

00:39:30.839 --> 00:39:39.060
but Anawrahta parried it with the Areindama
lance, and it reached not his body but pierced

00:39:39.060 --> 00:39:45.960
the pommel of his saddle, and when
Sokkate saw it, he was sore afraid and

00:39:45.960 --> 00:39:51.900
trembled.
Then said Anawrahta, ‘Brother, your turn is

00:39:51.900 --> 00:39:57.420
over. Now it is mine. Meet it as best you
can.’

00:39:57.420 --> 00:40:03.960
And he smote him and pierced him with
the Areindama lance so that it went in

00:40:03.960 --> 00:40:09.900
at the front and came out behind.
Sokkate’s horse ran away with him to

00:40:09.900 --> 00:40:14.420
the river, and there he died.

00:40:16.740 --> 00:40:21.660
This encounter, as rendered in the Glass
Palace Chronicle, feels like something

00:40:21.660 --> 00:40:27.720
out of the Arthurian legends, complete
with chivalric duels, legendary weapons

00:40:27.720 --> 00:40:33.480
of great power, and the fight to save a
woman's honor. We would be foolish to

00:40:33.480 --> 00:40:38.460
take it at face value as a historical
source, but it does give us a sense for

00:40:38.460 --> 00:40:43.800
the turbulent political landscape of
medieval Myanmar and what must have

00:40:43.800 --> 00:40:50.220
seemed like the clashing of great heroic
forces, the stuff of medieval romances, of

00:40:50.220 --> 00:40:56.579
myth and poetry.
With his brother defeated, Anawrahta took

00:40:56.579 --> 00:40:59.119
the throne.

00:41:01.859 --> 00:41:07.440
The chronicle records that Anawrahta was
riven with guilt over the death of his

00:41:07.440 --> 00:41:11.940
brother, and attempted to soothe his
conscience with the construction of

00:41:11.940 --> 00:41:18.079
great temples and works of
infrastructure throughout the kingdom.

00:41:18.320 --> 00:41:23.460
Anawrahta could not sleep for full six
months because he had slain his elder

00:41:23.460 --> 00:41:27.480
brother.
Then Sakra visited him with a dream,

00:41:27.480 --> 00:41:33.720
saying, ‘King, if thou wouldst mitigate
thine evil deed and sinning against thy

00:41:33.720 --> 00:41:39.960
elder brother, build many pagodas,
monasteries, and rest houses, and share

00:41:39.960 --> 00:41:46.859
the merit with thine elder brother.
Devise thou many wells, ponds, dams and

00:41:46.859 --> 00:41:52.140
ditches, fields and canals,
and share the merit with thine elder

00:41:52.140 --> 00:41:54.380
brother.’

00:41:56.119 --> 00:42:01.800
Archaeological evidence does show that
Anawrahta was indeed a prolific builder.

00:42:01.800 --> 00:42:07.859
Soon after coming to the throne in the
year 1044, he marched into the north to

00:42:07.859 --> 00:42:13.920
secure the northern border, and built 43
forts along the Irrawaddy River.

00:42:13.920 --> 00:42:18.359
The north was traditionally the gateway
to Burma, the lands through which all

00:42:18.359 --> 00:42:23.700
potential conquerors had previously
marched, and so it's clear he was keen to

00:42:23.700 --> 00:42:29.099
secure his land from invasion.
King Anawrahta built his network of

00:42:29.099 --> 00:42:34.500
fortresses as an armored corridor that
protected the valuable farmlands of the

00:42:34.500 --> 00:42:39.839
north and allowed his armies to move
quickly along well-supplied routes. He

00:42:39.839 --> 00:42:45.359
also fortified many of the towns in this
region, building strong city walls and

00:42:45.359 --> 00:42:49.079
garrisons,
while in the north he also built

00:42:49.079 --> 00:42:54.720
extensive irrigation canals and improved
the existing water infrastructure to get

00:42:54.720 --> 00:42:59.579
the most out of the land's potential, and
many of the canals and reservoirs that

00:42:59.579 --> 00:43:04.920
he built are still in use today, nearly a
thousand years later.

00:43:04.920 --> 00:43:09.720
Having secured the north to his
satisfaction, King Anawrahta turned his

00:43:09.720 --> 00:43:12.920
attention to the south.

00:43:15.500 --> 00:43:20.819
The coastal cities of southern Myanmar
were a clutter of independent

00:43:20.819 --> 00:43:25.619
city states, many of which had grown
wealthy on the traffic of trade, but

00:43:25.619 --> 00:43:30.119
passed by sea to the lands of India and
China.

00:43:30.119 --> 00:43:34.980
Passage through the mountains that
surround Myanmar was difficult, and so

00:43:34.980 --> 00:43:40.440
most goods that came into the country
flowed through these port towns.

00:43:40.440 --> 00:43:45.000
Having the good farmland was one thing,
but if Bagan had to keep paying the

00:43:45.000 --> 00:43:49.680
trade tariffs to these wealthy port
cities, it could never become the kind of

00:43:49.680 --> 00:43:54.060
great power that King Anawrahta clearly
dreamed of.

00:43:54.060 --> 00:43:59.339
According to the chronicles, he marched
south and first besieged the city of

00:43:59.339 --> 00:44:05.160
Thaton, as the Glass Palace Chronicle
records, although it's worth noting that

00:44:05.160 --> 00:44:10.200
in its typically exaggerated style, it's
probably multiplying the size of the

00:44:10.200 --> 00:44:18.359
army by at least a factor of a thousand.
He gathered all his mighty men of valor

00:44:18.359 --> 00:44:25.619
and marched by land and water.
By water he sent 800,000 boats and

00:44:25.619 --> 00:44:31.859
80 million fighting men. By land he made his
four generals march up front, while he

00:44:31.859 --> 00:44:35.280
marched forth with the main army in the
rear.

00:44:35.280 --> 00:44:40.440
His land force, it is said, contained
800,000 elephants, 8 million

00:44:40.440 --> 00:44:47.220
horses, and 18 million fighting
men. It is said that the line of troops

00:44:47.220 --> 00:44:52.020
was so long that when the first troops
of the army reached the frontier of

00:44:52.020 --> 00:44:57.859
Thaton territory, the rear guard still had
not departed from the capital.

00:44:57.900 --> 00:45:04.319
Seeing as this enormous force would far
exceed the population of Burma today and

00:45:04.319 --> 00:45:08.579
would have constituted about a quarter
of the world's total population at the

00:45:08.579 --> 00:45:13.140
time, we can assume this is an
exaggeration, but through exaggeration

00:45:13.140 --> 00:45:19.619
the chronicles make their point; the army
was no doubt impressive.

00:45:19.619 --> 00:45:24.540
With this force, he laid siege to the
city of Thaton, and after holding out for

00:45:24.540 --> 00:45:29.940
three months, the city capitulated.
From there, Anawrahta absorbed a number

00:45:29.940 --> 00:45:35.700
of the other coastal cities into what
was now becoming a true empire.

00:45:35.700 --> 00:45:40.760
By this time, the city of Bagan had
earned itself the Sanskrit title

00:45:40.760 --> 00:45:46.619
Arimaddana-pura, or the city that tramples
its enemies.

00:45:46.619 --> 00:45:51.660
Linking his capital to these coastal
cities meant that Bagan was now

00:45:51.660 --> 00:45:56.579
connected by sea routes to the great
centers of culture in India, and perhaps

00:45:56.579 --> 00:46:01.700
most crucially, with the island of Sri
Lanka.

00:46:04.619 --> 00:46:09.839
Sri Lanka is a nation off the coast of
Southern India, and for much of its

00:46:09.839 --> 00:46:14.040
history it has held on to a distinct
cultural character.

00:46:14.040 --> 00:46:19.859
While Buddhism, in its homeland of
mainland India, had mostly died out by

00:46:19.859 --> 00:46:25.560
this point, it had survived in Sri Lanka,
and this island nation had become the

00:46:25.560 --> 00:46:32.040
heartland of an ancient and austere form
of Buddhism known as Theravada.

00:46:32.040 --> 00:46:38.280
These new cultural links would transform
the culture and religion of Myanmar, and

00:46:38.280 --> 00:46:42.900
bring it into contact with new forms of
religious thought, and for King

00:46:42.900 --> 00:46:47.339
Anawrahta, freshly returned from the
battlefields of the south, they would

00:46:47.339 --> 00:46:53.220
provide an irresistible opportunity.
That was a chance to take on some of his

00:46:53.220 --> 00:46:59.700
oldest rivals, not an enemy kingdom or
empire, but an institution at the heart

00:46:59.700 --> 00:47:05.700
of his own kingdom,
the Buddhist church itself.

00:47:08.760 --> 00:47:15.480
For centuries, a strain of Buddhism known
as Ari Buddhism was the predominant form

00:47:15.480 --> 00:47:21.000
of religion in Myanmar.
Ari Buddhism was a hybrid form of

00:47:21.000 --> 00:47:26.579
Tibetan Buddhism and drew heavily on
traditional Burmese beliefs.

00:47:26.579 --> 00:47:31.440
As a result, their practices were quite
different to how we might picture a

00:47:31.440 --> 00:47:36.480
Buddhist monk today.
Unlike in most strains of Buddhism, the

00:47:36.480 --> 00:47:43.079
Ari monks grew beards and had long hair.
They wore blue-black robes dyed with

00:47:43.079 --> 00:47:49.140
indigo, drank alcohol, and practiced a
form of martial arts similar to boxing.

00:47:49.140 --> 00:47:53.280
They rode horses and even occasionally
went to war.

00:47:53.280 --> 00:47:58.319
They also worshiped the figure of the
Naga, a powerful form of snake spirit

00:47:58.319 --> 00:48:05.240
drawn from Hindu mythology, and built
statues depicting these in their temples.

00:48:05.240 --> 00:48:11.700
Owing to their long history in Burma, the
Ari monks enjoyed enormous power in the

00:48:11.700 --> 00:48:18.420
kingdom of Bagan. They owned vast estates
and held enormous stores of wealth.

00:48:18.420 --> 00:48:25.020
The Maya Yazawin, or Great Chronicle, even
records the scandalous claim that the

00:48:25.020 --> 00:48:30.180
monks were practicing a version of the
right of prima noctae, or first night,

00:48:30.180 --> 00:48:36.319
taking the virginity of brides before
their wedding nights.

00:48:36.480 --> 00:48:41.780
From then on, the sons and daughters of
all, starting with and including the king,

00:48:41.780 --> 00:48:47.099
ministers, generals, village
administrators, at that time when

00:48:47.099 --> 00:48:53.520
preparing to get married, must be sent to
the monks at nightfall to give the prime of

00:48:53.520 --> 00:48:59.040
their flower of virginity.
It was said that at dawn they were freed

00:48:59.040 --> 00:49:04.380
and allowed to wed. The king, having
matured, had become virtuous, and he was

00:49:04.380 --> 00:49:10.700
disconsolate to hear and observe such
wrongful practices.

00:49:11.280 --> 00:49:15.660
It's hard to know whether to take this
scurrilous claim seriously or whether

00:49:15.660 --> 00:49:21.960
it was a later piece of royal propaganda
designed to discredit these monks, but

00:49:21.960 --> 00:49:27.839
one thing was for certain; the Ari monks
were extremely powerful, and King Anawrahta

00:49:27.839 --> 00:49:32.760
had long dreamed of crushing their
establishment and remaking the church in

00:49:32.760 --> 00:49:37.440
a different image,
an image more closely under the control

00:49:37.440 --> 00:49:41.880
of the crown.
King Anawrahta would find the opportunity

00:49:41.880 --> 00:49:47.640
to do this when he met a visiting sage
named Shin Arahan.

00:49:47.640 --> 00:49:54.060
This Shin Arahan was from the south of
Myanmar, the region Anawrahta had recently

00:49:54.060 --> 00:50:00.119
absorbed. The sage had traveled in Sri
Lanka, and he told King Anawrahta of the

00:50:00.119 --> 00:50:04.560
merits of the different branch of
Buddhism practiced there, a branch that

00:50:04.560 --> 00:50:09.420
claimed to be the closest to the
original teachings of the Buddha. This

00:50:09.420 --> 00:50:14.780
was the Theravada Buddhism incubated in
the grand Sri Lankan cities of

00:50:14.780 --> 00:50:21.060
Anuradhapura and Polonnaruwa.
This strain of Buddhism emphasizes

00:50:21.060 --> 00:50:27.599
priests living simple lives, living by
begging, not eating after midday, refusing

00:50:27.599 --> 00:50:31.859
all intoxicants, and not even touching
money.

00:50:31.859 --> 00:50:37.859
Considering the seemingly uncontrollable
nature of Burma's Ari monks, to King

00:50:37.859 --> 00:50:44.640
Anawrahta, this must have sounded ideal.
The Glass Palace Chronicle recounts the

00:50:44.640 --> 00:50:49.640
king's conversion as a spiritual
epiphany.

00:50:49.800 --> 00:50:56.000
The king was full of joy and rapture, and
spoke again, entreating him, my Lord,

00:50:56.000 --> 00:51:01.920
preach me somewhat -- yes, but a little -- of
the law preached by the lord, the master,

00:51:01.920 --> 00:51:06.839
and Shin Arahan preached the law,
beginning with the things not to be

00:51:06.839 --> 00:51:11.640
neglected.
Then the king's heart was full of faith,

00:51:11.640 --> 00:51:17.220
steadfast and immovable.
Faith sank into him as oil filtered a

00:51:17.220 --> 00:51:22.880
hundred times soaks into cotton a
hundred times teased.

00:51:23.220 --> 00:51:29.040
Perhaps King Anawrahta was genuinely moved
by the sage's teachings, but it's clear

00:51:29.040 --> 00:51:33.780
he also spotted an opportunity.
If he brought this new branch of

00:51:33.780 --> 00:51:38.760
Buddhism to his kingdom, he could weaken
the hold of the Ari monks.

00:51:38.760 --> 00:51:44.780
So, King Anawrahta went to war with the
church.

00:51:45.020 --> 00:51:49.800
First, the king went after the monks’
ability to recruit.

00:51:49.800 --> 00:51:55.440
He brought in new laws that meant that
common people were no longer obliged to

00:51:55.440 --> 00:52:00.180
give up their young children to become
monks, as they had been before.

00:52:00.180 --> 00:52:05.760
Next he changed the law to remove the
punishment for those who deserted their

00:52:05.760 --> 00:52:11.520
life as a monk. As a result, many
dissatisfied monks simply hung up their

00:52:11.520 --> 00:52:17.640
robes and left to do something else.
Bit by bit, Anawrahta chipped away at the

00:52:17.640 --> 00:52:21.660
monks’ power with every tool at his
disposal.

00:52:21.660 --> 00:52:27.359
There were, of course, those who fought
the changes. Anawrahta banished thousands

00:52:27.359 --> 00:52:33.119
of monks who resisted his reforms. Many
of these fled to the nearby volcano of

00:52:33.119 --> 00:52:39.119
Mount Popa or east into the narrow
forested valleys of the Shan Hills, and

00:52:39.119 --> 00:52:43.200
while they were never completely wiped
out, they would never again wield the

00:52:43.200 --> 00:52:48.720
same power in the kingdom.
To celebrate the conversion of his land,

00:52:48.720 --> 00:52:54.900
Anawrahta sent an envoy to Sri Lanka and
asked rather boldly that their most

00:52:54.900 --> 00:53:00.540
precious relic, a tooth belonging to the
Buddha himself, be sent to Myanmar to be

00:53:00.540 --> 00:53:06.900
placed in one of his great temples.
The Sri Lankans understandably refused,

00:53:06.900 --> 00:53:12.420
but at the last moment they remembered
that they had a spare, and the envoy was

00:53:12.420 --> 00:53:17.760
sent back to Burma with what they were
told was another tooth of the Buddha.

00:53:17.760 --> 00:53:23.339
Like the small fragments of wood taken
from the cross used at Jesus's

00:53:23.339 --> 00:53:28.500
crucifixion that showed up in churches
across Medieval Europe, teeth of the

00:53:28.500 --> 00:53:33.599
Buddha had a way of multiplying in
Southeast Asia according to the needs of

00:53:33.599 --> 00:53:38.460
the people.
But it was good enough for Anawrahta. When

00:53:38.460 --> 00:53:43.260
the new tooth relic arrived in the
capital by boat, the king himself waded

00:53:43.260 --> 00:53:47.119
out into the river to meet it. Anawrahta

00:53:52.339 --> 00:53:58.260
was an effective ruler, but at times he
could also be uncompromising and harsh.

00:53:58.260 --> 00:54:02.940
While he was often able to achieve what
he wanted in his kingdom, he did this

00:54:02.940 --> 00:54:08.460
largely at the expense of his popularity,
and this is nowhere more apparent than

00:54:08.460 --> 00:54:15.319
in the story that is remembered as the
tragic romance of his son, Kyansittha.

00:54:16.579 --> 00:54:21.680
Kyansittha was a great general and had led his
father's armies into battle many times,

00:54:21.680 --> 00:54:26.700
and when the people in the region of
Pegu complained about raiders destroying

00:54:26.700 --> 00:54:31.859
their homes and stealing their animals,
the king sent Kyansittha to deal with

00:54:31.859 --> 00:54:36.000
the situation.
The story goes that the prince saw off

00:54:36.000 --> 00:54:40.680
the raiders, and the people of Pegu were
so grateful that they sent him home with

00:54:40.680 --> 00:54:46.200
various gifts for the king, gifts of gold,
hairs belonging to the Buddha, and a

00:54:46.200 --> 00:54:50.700
beautiful young woman named U Khin,
intended to be offered to the king as a

00:54:50.700 --> 00:54:53.880
bride. It
was on the journey home Prince Kyansittha

00:54:53.880 --> 00:55:01.079
and U Khin fell in love.
When Anawrahta found out about this

00:55:01.079 --> 00:55:06.599
Arthurian betrayal, he exiled his own son,
who was forced to flee across the

00:55:06.599 --> 00:55:12.300
countryside of Myanmar and go into
hiding. This story, with its forbidden

00:55:12.300 --> 00:55:17.940
love, betrayal, and dramatic finale, has
proved irresistible to generations of

00:55:17.940 --> 00:55:22.619
playwrights, songwriters, and poets in
Myanmar.

00:55:22.619 --> 00:55:27.839
But ultimately, it seems that this
uncompromising nature would finally lead

00:55:27.839 --> 00:55:35.099
to the downfall of King Anawrahta.
On the 11th of April, 1077, the king was

00:55:35.099 --> 00:55:40.200
riding through the outskirts of Bagan on
the back of his elephant.

00:55:40.200 --> 00:55:45.359
The chronicles record that a tree spirit
that the king had previously displeased

00:55:45.359 --> 00:55:50.940
appeared in the guise of a wild buffalo
and gored him to death, and then demons

00:55:50.940 --> 00:55:55.440
took away his body
so that it was never found.

00:55:55.440 --> 00:56:00.359
Much more likely is that the king's
unpopularity finally got the better of

00:56:00.359 --> 00:56:05.579
him and he was ambushed and killed by a
group of rivals who ensured that no

00:56:05.579 --> 00:56:11.400
evidence remained of their crime.
The chronicles recall his death with

00:56:11.400 --> 00:56:17.940
great sorrow.
Thus this noble king, full of glory, might

00:56:17.940 --> 00:56:25.079
of arm and dominion, who for full 33
years of royal prosperity had advanced

00:56:25.079 --> 00:56:30.420
the welfare of the religion, his own
welfare, and that of the generations of

00:56:30.420 --> 00:56:37.200
his sons, grandsons, and great-grandsons,
died at the age of 75. About the time of

00:56:37.200 --> 00:56:43.140
his death, bees clave to the throne door
of the palace, an ogre laughed from the

00:56:43.140 --> 00:56:49.559
top of the Tharaba gate, and luster of
the royal sword faded, and a vulture

00:56:49.559 --> 00:56:54.800
alighted on the palace.
After the death of the great king

00:56:54.800 --> 00:57:00.480
Anawrahta, his son Sawlu took the throne
at the age of 26.

00:57:00.480 --> 00:57:04.800
Although not particularly young by the
standards of royalty, he would soon gain

00:57:04.800 --> 00:57:11.280
the title Min Lulin, or the Boy King, on
account of his inexperienced and naive

00:57:11.280 --> 00:57:16.319
style of ruling.
After only five years of mismanaging the

00:57:16.319 --> 00:57:21.599
kingdom, he faced a rebellion in the
south among the Mon people who lived in

00:57:21.599 --> 00:57:25.380
the coastal cities that his father had
conquered.

00:57:25.380 --> 00:57:30.599
For not the first time, the chronicles
recall a quite unlikely-sounding version

00:57:30.599 --> 00:57:34.559
of events.
In this version of the story, the king

00:57:34.559 --> 00:57:39.839
Sawlu lost at a game of dice with one of
his nobles, a childhood friend of his

00:57:39.839 --> 00:57:46.619
named Yamankan, and in a fit of sore
losing rage, he dared the noble to rebel

00:57:46.619 --> 00:57:51.480
against him.
One day, the king and Yamankan played at

00:57:51.480 --> 00:57:57.300
dice, and Yamankan won, and he rose up
and clapped his elbows.

00:57:57.300 --> 00:58:03.839
Said King Sawlu, ‘You have won a mere game
of dice, and you dare to arise and clap

00:58:03.839 --> 00:58:08.640
your elbows.
If you are a man, rebel with Pegu, your

00:58:08.640 --> 00:58:13.079
province.’
‘In truth?’ asked Yamankan.

00:58:13.079 --> 00:58:20.480
‘We kings,’ said the king,
‘should we utter anything but truth?’

00:58:20.880 --> 00:58:26.640
According to the chronicle, Yamankan
promptly returned to Pegu and started a

00:58:26.640 --> 00:58:31.160
rebellion, as the king had suggested.

00:58:31.500 --> 00:58:36.780
While this account may not exactly be
true, it probably does contain some truth

00:58:36.780 --> 00:58:42.059
about the character of King Sawlu, who by
all accounts had a petty and childish

00:58:42.059 --> 00:58:46.079
nature and seems to have treated the
business of ruling as though it were

00:58:46.079 --> 00:58:50.760
little more than a game.
Now facing an open rebellion, the

00:58:50.760 --> 00:58:55.980
childish King Sawlu turned to someone
that his father had long ago exiled for

00:58:55.980 --> 00:59:00.059
the crime of falling in love with a
woman promised to him.

00:59:00.059 --> 00:59:06.359
That is his half-brother, the romantic
hero of songs and poetry, the man named

00:59:06.359 --> 00:59:09.140
Kyansittha. Kyansittha

00:59:10.819 --> 00:59:16.200
came out of exile and agreed to help the
childish king lead his armies against

00:59:16.200 --> 00:59:21.359
the rebellion in the south,
but King Sawlu would prove to have no

00:59:21.359 --> 00:59:27.000
better judgment on the battlefield than
off it, and he would be fooled one day by

00:59:27.000 --> 00:59:30.260
a devious ploy. King Sawlu and Kyansittha

00:59:33.319 --> 00:59:40.099
encamped when they reached the island of
Pye-dawta, saying, ‘It is too late today;

00:59:40.099 --> 00:59:46.200
tomorrow we shall fight.’
Then in the dim moonlight, Yamankan

00:59:46.200 --> 00:59:49.500
came forth and provoked them to do
battle.

00:59:49.500 --> 00:59:55.980
So, they followed and fought without heed
or observation, and the King Sawlu,

00:59:55.980 --> 01:00:01.740
thinking that an elephant figure sat in
the mud was a real elephant,

01:00:01.740 --> 01:00:07.740
set forth to fight, and the royal
elephant he was riding fell into the mud

01:00:07.740 --> 01:00:12.720
and stuck.
King Sawlu climbed down from his back

01:00:12.720 --> 01:00:20.099
and ran, and entering a hole in the
banyan tree in the forest, hid there, and

01:00:20.099 --> 01:00:25.680
his elephant was captured, and the whole
army was despoiled and fled.

01:00:25.680 --> 01:00:29.420
There was none to stop them.

01:00:29.760 --> 01:00:35.160
Sawlu was soon found hiding in the banyan
tree and was taken into captivity by the

01:00:35.160 --> 01:00:39.900
rebel Yamankan. According to another
slightly fantastical episode in the

01:00:39.900 --> 01:00:45.420
chronicles, Sawlu did actually have one
chance to escape when the hero

01:00:45.420 --> 01:00:49.920
Kyansittha personally snuck into the enemy
camp to rescue him.

01:00:49.920 --> 01:00:55.740
But Sawlu feared that Kyansittha secretly
wanted to kill him, and he refused to go

01:00:55.740 --> 01:01:00.299
with his rescuer.
He believed that the rebel Yamankan,

01:01:00.299 --> 01:01:04.920
who had been his friend and who he had
played many games of dice with, would not

01:01:04.920 --> 01:01:12.040
harm him. And he stole him from the place where he was kept. Now while Kyansittha bare him on his

01:01:12.059 --> 01:01:16.319
shoulder, Sawlu thought,
‘Kyansittha is one whom my father has

01:01:16.319 --> 01:01:22.859
injured, whom I have injured. I fear he
steals me away to kill me. But Yamankan

01:01:22.859 --> 01:01:26.880
is son of my tutor; surely he will not
kill me.’

01:01:26.880 --> 01:01:34.559
Sawlu yelled out, ‘Kyansittha is stealing me!’
Kyansittha exclaimed, ‘Then die you fool. Die

01:01:34.559 --> 01:01:40.079
the death of a dog at the hands of these
scum,’ flung him down, and ran for his life.

01:01:40.079 --> 01:01:46.079
He swam across the Irrawaddy and
eventually made back to safety.

01:01:46.079 --> 01:01:51.540
But like many of his other calculations,
Sawlu's gamble didn't pay off.

01:01:51.540 --> 01:01:57.960
Fearing more escape attempts, Yamankan
had the king killed in April of the year

01:01:57.960 --> 01:02:03.059
1084.
In the game of life, it seems the king

01:02:03.059 --> 01:02:07.579
Sawlu was always rolling ones.

01:02:09.299 --> 01:02:14.040
After the death of Sawlu, Kyansittha
continued to lead the royal armies of

01:02:14.040 --> 01:02:19.500
Bagan against Yamankan's rebellion, and
the rebel leader fled south on the river

01:02:19.500 --> 01:02:26.220
on his opulent golden barge.
Kyansittha sent a hunter named Ya-sin to

01:02:26.220 --> 01:02:32.460
follow him and to kill him if he could.
The chronicle recounts what happened

01:02:32.460 --> 01:02:35.059
next.

01:02:36.180 --> 01:02:41.160
Ya-sin in the hunter caught him up
below Ywatha, and he climbed a fig

01:02:41.160 --> 01:02:44.819
tree and uttered lovely notes like the
voice of a bird.

01:02:44.819 --> 01:02:49.740
When Yamankan heard that sound, he
opened the door of the golden raft

01:02:49.740 --> 01:02:54.900
and looked, saying,
‘What bird is that uttering notes so sweet

01:02:54.900 --> 01:03:01.020
and wonderful?’
Now he had but one good eye, and Ya-sin

01:03:01.020 --> 01:03:07.740
the hunter, from the place where he
waited peeping, drew his bow and shot and

01:03:07.740 --> 01:03:13.220
hit the eye of Yamankan,
and he died.

01:03:14.700 --> 01:03:22.880
Now the once-exiled Kyansittha was the
only person in line for the throne.

01:03:30.440 --> 01:03:39.319
Kyansittha came to the throne on the 21st of April,
1084, and assumed the title Sri Tribhuvanaditya

01:03:39.319 --> 01:03:45.359
Dhammaraja, which means something like
fortunate Buddhist king, son of the three

01:03:45.359 --> 01:03:50.220
worlds.
In many ways, he was the perfect uniting

01:03:50.220 --> 01:03:55.260
figure for the country after such a
period of violence and division.

01:03:55.260 --> 01:03:59.760
While in exile from his father, he had
lived for seven years in the southern

01:03:59.760 --> 01:04:05.579
Mon region among those coastal cities,
and there he had developed a genuine

01:04:05.579 --> 01:04:12.540
love for the Mon people and culture.
Kyansittha invited Mon nobles to court and

01:04:12.540 --> 01:04:16.920
appointed them to high positions in the
kingdom, some of whom had been part of

01:04:16.920 --> 01:04:22.799
the rebellion only years before.
The result of this generous approach was

01:04:22.799 --> 01:04:28.260
a long period of peace in Myanmar, and
with that peace came a period of great

01:04:28.260 --> 01:04:33.599
prosperity.
During this time, the capital city of

01:04:33.599 --> 01:04:39.000
Bagan grew to previously unimaginable
size and wealth.

01:04:39.000 --> 01:04:43.920
The population boomed as a result of the
growing agricultural potential of the

01:04:43.920 --> 01:04:50.000
city, but Bagan also attracted people
from across the region; artists, sculptors,

01:04:50.000 --> 01:04:56.400
masons, architects, monks, scholars, and
teachers.

01:04:56.400 --> 01:05:01.020
We can track the booming of the city in
the ever-increasing number of temples

01:05:01.020 --> 01:05:06.240
that were built in the 300 years after
the reign of King Anawrahta, each of which

01:05:06.240 --> 01:05:12.540
we can reliably date with carbon dating.
During this time, as many as 4,000

01:05:12.540 --> 01:05:16.680
temples were built, along with
thousands more brick structures

01:05:16.680 --> 01:05:22.500
supporting them.
Many of these temples had vast stupas or

01:05:22.500 --> 01:05:27.720
domed shrines at their center, and the
effort and expense of constructing these

01:05:27.720 --> 01:05:32.520
must have been enormous.
This building effort would have required

01:05:32.520 --> 01:05:37.980
an army of masons and carpenters,
plasterers and sculptors, gold and

01:05:37.980 --> 01:05:43.920
silversmiths, either paid in cash or
working in exchange for food, animals, and

01:05:43.920 --> 01:05:49.079
land. These artists would have required
the support of an even larger array of

01:05:49.079 --> 01:05:54.720
supporting industries. Masons required
brickbuilders who required firewood

01:05:54.720 --> 01:05:59.640
brought by lumberjacks and porters. The
sculptors of countless statues of the

01:05:59.640 --> 01:06:03.540
Buddha needed miners of marble and
dolerite

01:06:03.540 --> 01:06:08.280
and elephant trainers to transport the
heavy stone blocks,

01:06:08.280 --> 01:06:14.099
and all of them needed rice, fruit,
vegetables, meat, and game, and of course

01:06:14.099 --> 01:06:19.680
the alcoholic spirits brewed from rice
or the foaming toddy made from the

01:06:19.680 --> 01:06:24.960
fermented sap of the palm tree.
With work to be had in every corner of

01:06:24.960 --> 01:06:29.640
the city, people traveled for thousands
of kilometers to find employment in the

01:06:29.640 --> 01:06:35.539
enormous construction site that the city
of Bagan had become.

01:06:36.619 --> 01:06:42.240
At one point, the Glass Palace Chronicle
lists the professions of people who were

01:06:42.240 --> 01:06:47.460
deported from a conquered city during
the reign of King Anawrahta, and from it we

01:06:47.460 --> 01:06:51.299
get a sense of all the ways that someone
could make their livelihood in the city

01:06:51.299 --> 01:06:56.220
of Bagan.
Thereafter he sent away separately,

01:06:56.220 --> 01:07:04.079
without mixing, such men as were skilled
in carving, turning, and painting; masons,

01:07:04.079 --> 01:07:10.680
molders of plaster and flower patterns,
blacksmiths, silversmiths, braziers,

01:07:10.680 --> 01:07:17.520
founders of gongs and symbols, filigree
flower workers, doctors and trainers of

01:07:17.520 --> 01:07:24.440
elephants and horses, makers of shields
round and embossed, men skilled in frying,

01:07:24.440 --> 01:07:32.099
parching, baking, and frizzling, yakin
hairdressers, and men cunning in perfumes,

01:07:32.099 --> 01:07:38.660
odors, flowers, and the juices of flowers.

01:07:39.680 --> 01:07:45.599
From the small fortress capital that
it had once been, Bagan expanded to fill an

01:07:45.599 --> 01:07:51.000
area of more than 100 square kilometers,
or more than twice the size of ancient

01:07:51.000 --> 01:07:54.480
Rome.
Estimates for the population around this

01:07:54.480 --> 01:08:01.079
time range as high as 400,000 people
living in the city alone.

01:08:01.079 --> 01:08:06.000
During this time, many of the largest
temples were constructed, and the largest

01:08:06.000 --> 01:08:11.339
of all is the temple known as the
Thatbyinnyu Temple.

01:08:11.339 --> 01:08:18.000
Consecrated in the year 1144, the vast
spired pagoda of this temple rises to a

01:08:18.000 --> 01:08:22.799
height of over 61 meters, or more than 20
stories.

01:08:22.799 --> 01:08:28.440
Another temple nearby is called the
Ananda Temple, and it rises to a height

01:08:28.440 --> 01:08:34.020
of 51 meters. This temple served not only
as a place of worship, but also as a

01:08:34.020 --> 01:08:39.239
monastery and a library. The temple's
first and second floors were used as the

01:08:39.239 --> 01:08:44.819
residents of monks, while the third floor
was used to hold images. The fourth floor

01:08:44.819 --> 01:08:50.640
was used to store manuscripts and books,
and the fifth and top floor stored the

01:08:50.640 --> 01:08:54.779
precious relics.
The building of temples in Bagan was

01:08:54.779 --> 01:08:58.799
seen as the ultimate form of devotion
that a king could engage in.

01:08:58.799 --> 01:09:04.140
When one later king Alaungsithu
dedicated the completing of the Shwegugyi

01:09:04.140 --> 01:09:09.120
pagoda, he spoke the following
prayer in which he envisions the temples

01:09:09.120 --> 01:09:15.420
as a kind of grand infrastructure of the
soul as a bridge across Samsara, or the

01:09:15.420 --> 01:09:21.719
endless cycle of rebirth, and towards
eternal enlightenment.

01:09:21.719 --> 01:09:30.140
By this abundant merit, I desire here nor
hereafter no angelic pomp of Brahmas,

01:09:30.140 --> 01:09:37.560
Suras, Maras, nor the state and splendors
of a monarch, nay not even to be the

01:09:37.560 --> 01:09:43.799
pupil of the conqueror. But I would build
a causeway sheer across the river of

01:09:43.799 --> 01:09:50.400
Samsara, and all folk would speed across
thereby until they reached the Blessed

01:09:50.400 --> 01:09:54.060
City.
These temples were held in the highest

01:09:54.060 --> 01:09:59.420
reverence. One of the inscriptions at the
unfinished Mingun Pahtodawgyi

01:09:59.420 --> 01:10:05.219
temple, built some time after the Bagan
era, contains the following blessings for

01:10:05.219 --> 01:10:10.080
those who respect the sanctity of the
temple, as well as a series of blistering

01:10:10.080 --> 01:10:14.760
curses against any who damage or
desecrate it.

01:10:14.760 --> 01:10:21.300
Who favors and upholds like me the gift
of faith which I thus offer with all my

01:10:21.300 --> 01:10:27.540
heart? Be he my son, grandson, or any
future king who comes after me, queens,

01:10:27.540 --> 01:10:33.060
princes, royal ministers high or low, may
he be favored above others with the

01:10:33.060 --> 01:10:39.719
wheel of treasure. May he be endued like
King Mandhata with glory, majesty, and

01:10:39.719 --> 01:10:44.340
power.
But whoever spoils even so much as an

01:10:44.340 --> 01:10:49.920
oil lamp here, may he be oppressed with
the eight dangers, the ten punishments,

01:10:49.920 --> 01:10:57.120
the 32 results of karma, the eight
calamities, the 96 diseases. May he be

01:10:57.120 --> 01:11:01.800
suddenly overtaken with a great
affliction which a thousand doctors may

01:11:01.800 --> 01:11:07.500
not avail to cure. Having suffered thus
for long, generation after generation,

01:11:07.500 --> 01:11:14.040
when his bodily elements dissolve, may he
suffer by going in and out among the

01:11:14.040 --> 01:11:20.400
eight chief Hells, and the twelve minor
Hells, and the 40 limbos of Yama and

01:11:20.400 --> 01:11:27.239
Lokika. May he suffer with the hosts of
demons, titans, and hungry ghosts. Even if

01:11:27.239 --> 01:11:33.719
he survive all these sufferings, may he
revisit five thousand times these lands

01:11:33.719 --> 01:11:43.080
in the form of a boneless and miserable
creature, a ghost, a worm, a water leech.

01:11:43.080 --> 01:11:49.080
While royal annals like the Glass Palace
Chronicle are extremely detailed on the

01:11:49.080 --> 01:11:54.000
comings and goings of Bagan's kings,
unfortunately they have very little to

01:11:54.000 --> 01:11:58.860
say about what life was like for the
average person during this time.

01:11:58.860 --> 01:12:04.199
For a picture of daily life for the
average person in Bagan, we can turn to

01:12:04.199 --> 01:12:09.179
the pages of the classical poetry of
Myanmar.

01:12:09.179 --> 01:12:14.640
Myanmar has had a great poetic tradition
for centuries, and the time of Bagan was

01:12:14.640 --> 01:12:20.280
no exception. Many poets flourished among
its scholarly communities, in its temples

01:12:20.280 --> 01:12:25.020
and royal courts, and the manuscripts
that these scholars produced were

01:12:25.020 --> 01:12:30.719
exceptionally valuable.
Records show that in the year 1273, a

01:12:30.719 --> 01:12:37.020
complete set of the Buddhist texts known
as the Tripitaka, cost up to 3,000 kyats,

01:12:37.020 --> 01:12:43.860
or nearly 50 kilos of silver. That would
be enough to buy more than 5,000 acres

01:12:43.860 --> 01:12:50.280
of riceland, four large monasteries, or
150 slaves.

01:12:50.280 --> 01:12:55.800
The exceeding expense of these texts
meant that literacy was never widespread,

01:12:55.800 --> 01:13:00.960
and most common people would not learn
to read or write.

01:13:00.960 --> 01:13:07.739
One 15th century poet named Shin
Maharattathara wrote a poem that describes

01:13:07.739 --> 01:13:12.560
the qualities required by a man of
learning.

01:13:16.580 --> 01:13:23.159
If one does not try with the eagerness
of a daring eagle that firmly catches a

01:13:23.159 --> 01:13:28.980
hen, if one does not study and ponder,
does not question and does not discuss

01:13:28.980 --> 01:13:35.820
and knows only how to read palm leaves,
how can one become a well-known man of

01:13:35.820 --> 01:13:42.540
letters? Like a cat eating a shrimp with
special enjoyment, a learner must study

01:13:42.540 --> 01:13:49.199
all texts. He must become sharp as teeth
of a saw penetrating deeply into all

01:13:49.199 --> 01:13:54.960
discussed matters, to unravel the subject
from beginning to end without fear like

01:13:54.960 --> 01:13:57.320
a lion.

01:14:05.340 --> 01:14:11.280
One area that these poets can really
educate us about is in the realm of food.

01:14:11.280 --> 01:14:17.640
A 17th century poet named Wungyi Padethayaza
gives a description of the diet of an

01:14:17.640 --> 01:14:22.739
ordinary farmer who supplements his
meals of rice and curry with various

01:14:22.739 --> 01:14:28.400
kinds of animal life that he finds in
his fields.

01:14:30.199 --> 01:14:36.420
The peasant plows his field, and in his
rice fields are water-filled holes, home

01:14:36.420 --> 01:14:41.719
to many small crabs. Tossing these into
his shoulder basket together with frogs,

01:14:41.719 --> 01:14:48.600
snails, su-pou plants, kazoon and kinhon
leaves, and pilo, all for his curry.

01:14:48.600 --> 01:14:54.719
Stoopingly, he goes back home.
Sweet and juicy is the curry, cooked on

01:14:54.719 --> 01:14:59.640
arrival and laid out quickly with kyan-
-hing and kee-wet-na vegetables. The rice is

01:14:59.640 --> 01:15:05.540
hot, and the curry is hopped with pungent
spices that make one suck, tht, tht, tht.

01:15:05.540 --> 01:15:11.580
Scooping sizable handfuls, bending he
eats, surrounded on all sides by his sons

01:15:11.580 --> 01:15:16.199
and grandsons.

01:15:17.340 --> 01:15:21.900
Another source of information is the
painted walls of certain temples and

01:15:21.900 --> 01:15:27.659
pagodas in Bagan, which show us a little
of the city's dress styles too, at least

01:15:27.659 --> 01:15:30.500
among the wealthy.

01:15:30.960 --> 01:15:36.300
The people's costumes in these paintings
are combinations of Indian and Chinese

01:15:36.300 --> 01:15:41.880
cultures. They wore long dresses and
shawls, with most of the materials made

01:15:41.880 --> 01:15:47.480
of silk and cotton. Both men and women
wore bangles on their wrists and arms,

01:15:47.480 --> 01:15:54.120
necklaces and foot chains, and seemed to
have worn jeweled belts on their waists.

01:15:54.120 --> 01:15:59.340
One prominent cultural practice among
many ethnic groups in Burma was

01:15:59.340 --> 01:16:04.380
extensive tattooing, especially of the
legs, and this would likely have been

01:16:04.380 --> 01:16:10.820
evident on the streets of Bagan.
One European visitor in the 19th century

01:16:10.820 --> 01:16:16.320
commented on this practice.
Every male Berman is tattooed in his

01:16:16.320 --> 01:16:21.179
boyhood from the middle to his knees. In
fact, he has a pair of breeches tattooed

01:16:21.179 --> 01:16:24.179
on him.
The pattern is a fanciful medley of

01:16:24.179 --> 01:16:29.640
animals and arabesques.
But ultimately, the people who lived out

01:16:29.640 --> 01:16:34.920
their countless lives in the streets and
alleys of Bagan, farming rice and

01:16:34.920 --> 01:16:40.020
cucumbers, tending to their animals and
constructing the temples, have been

01:16:40.020 --> 01:16:44.699
forgotten, and it's only the raging
dramas of the Royal Court that have been

01:16:44.699 --> 01:16:50.219
remembered in any true detail. In the
coming centuries, those dramas would

01:16:50.219 --> 01:16:55.880
reach a fever pitch.

01:16:58.500 --> 01:17:04.500
Throughout his reign, King Kyansittha
struggled to have a son, so much so that

01:17:04.500 --> 01:17:09.360
he almost lost hope.
Without a son to provide a clear line of

01:17:09.360 --> 01:17:13.560
inheritance, the kingdom could be thrust
into civil war.

01:17:13.560 --> 01:17:19.080
When a son was finally born to him in
the year 1090, he was so overjoyed that

01:17:19.080 --> 01:17:24.719
he immediately crowned the baby boy king,
and stepped down to serve only as his

01:17:24.719 --> 01:17:29.219
regent.
The boy was called Sithu.

01:17:29.219 --> 01:17:35.159
Kyansittha would die 22 years later, and
his son Sithu took the throne with no

01:17:35.159 --> 01:17:39.360
opposition.
Like his father, he would be an excellent

01:17:39.360 --> 01:17:47.179
ruler in terms of politics and warfare,
but it seems he wasn't the best parent.

01:17:47.580 --> 01:17:52.440
He had several sons, but before they
could come of age, it became clear that

01:17:52.440 --> 01:17:58.560
for one reason or another, his oldest son
was not suitable for the throne, and so,

01:17:58.560 --> 01:18:03.900
Sithu had him banished.
The second son, who would go on to take

01:18:03.900 --> 01:18:09.900
the throne, was a man named Narathu, and he
has been remembered to history as a

01:18:09.900 --> 01:18:16.080
tyrant and a psychopath.
When King Sithu finally fell ill in his

01:18:16.080 --> 01:18:23.340
old age, this impatient son took the
opportunity to speed up his inheritance.

01:18:23.340 --> 01:18:31.199
Now when he reached the age of 101, he
fell grievously sick. His son Narathu

01:18:31.199 --> 01:18:36.840
removed him from the throne and kept him
within Schwegu pagoda.

01:18:36.840 --> 01:18:42.960
The king recovered consciousness a
while and said, ‘This is not my palace.

01:18:42.960 --> 01:18:48.120
Whose trickery is this?’
The king was convulsed with anger;

01:18:48.120 --> 01:18:56.040
his whole body burned like fire. Then his
son Narathu thought, ‘If the king arises

01:18:56.040 --> 01:19:02.100
from his sickness, I shall be utterly
destroyed.’ So with clothes and garments,

01:19:02.100 --> 01:19:07.699
he pressed down the king
until he died.

01:19:08.840 --> 01:19:13.260
Narathu wanted to take the throne for
himself, but there was still the problem

01:19:13.260 --> 01:19:18.300
of his banished older brother.
He devised a plan to place his brother

01:19:18.300 --> 01:19:22.980
on the throne first to make things look
a little less suspicious, but of course

01:19:22.980 --> 01:19:29.460
he would not sit there for long.
When he reached Leppan Port, Narathu,

01:19:29.460 --> 01:19:35.219
according to the oath he had sworn, went
down to the boat and, shouldering his

01:19:35.219 --> 01:19:41.340
brother's sword, he raised and set him on
the throne. After his anointing, his food

01:19:41.340 --> 01:19:45.800
was poisoned, and that night he died.

01:19:48.300 --> 01:19:53.640
With all these threats dealt with, King
Narathu ascended to the throne himself,

01:19:53.640 --> 01:19:59.100
and he would rule in a predictably
tyrannical style, as the Glass Palace

01:19:59.100 --> 01:20:04.860
Chronicle recalls.
King Narathu had once been the demon

01:20:04.860 --> 01:20:09.780
guardian of a mountain who had shaded
the Lord, so he was great in glory, might,

01:20:09.780 --> 01:20:15.420
and dominion. His ministers, both great
and small, his followers, and all the

01:20:15.420 --> 01:20:21.780
people stood in fear and awe of him. He
raged furiously with wrath and pride. The

01:20:21.780 --> 01:20:27.900
king was brutal and savage. His queens,
concubines, and handmaids stood in fear

01:20:27.900 --> 01:20:33.480
and awe of him and loved him not, but
hated him and cursed him in their hearts.

01:20:33.480 --> 01:20:39.300
All the inhabitants of the kingdom
starved in toil and sweat, and many forts,

01:20:39.300 --> 01:20:46.500
villages, and domains were ruined.
Seemingly desperate to assuage his guilt

01:20:46.500 --> 01:20:51.659
for his heinous actions, Narathu
increasingly isolated himself in his

01:20:51.659 --> 01:20:56.460
palace and ordered the construction of
what he intended to be the largest and

01:20:56.460 --> 01:21:03.360
most ambitious of all of Bagan's temples,
known as the Dhammayangyi Temple.

01:21:03.360 --> 01:21:08.640
But Narathu would not live to see this
great temple completed. It's not clear

01:21:08.640 --> 01:21:13.800
who gave the order, but Narathu was in his
palace one day when he was approached by

01:21:13.800 --> 01:21:18.780
a group of eight men dressed as monks.
When the men got close enough to the

01:21:18.780 --> 01:21:23.159
king, they drew their daggers and each
stabbed him. When they were sure that he

01:21:23.159 --> 01:21:28.380
was dead, in a kind of suicide pact, they
turned their knives on each other and

01:21:28.380 --> 01:21:33.900
themselves, as the Glass Palace Chronicle
records.

01:21:33.900 --> 01:21:39.480
They ascended the palace and drew nigh
the king, encircling him under guise of

01:21:39.480 --> 01:21:44.159
presenting the conch and neza grass, and
they pierced the king with the sword

01:21:44.159 --> 01:21:50.040
until he died. Thereafter they pursued
the minister Theiddika to pierce him, but

01:21:50.040 --> 01:21:53.880
they could not catch him.
Then they pierced their own bodies with

01:21:53.880 --> 01:21:58.280
the sword and died, all eight of them.

01:21:59.580 --> 01:22:04.679
The reign of King Narathu did great
damage to the kingdom of Bagan and

01:22:04.679 --> 01:22:09.540
harmed its reputation abroad.
But in the end it wasn't tyranny,

01:22:09.540 --> 01:22:14.699
rebellion, or kingly blundering that
brought down the empire.

01:22:14.699 --> 01:22:20.699
After several more royal assassinations,
coups and throne seizures, the kingdom

01:22:20.699 --> 01:22:26.159
would eventually return to peace under
the long reign of a king named Narapatisithu,

01:22:26.159 --> 01:22:30.300
who would reign until the year
1211.

01:22:30.300 --> 01:22:34.800
But all this time, the forces that would
eventually tear this great city of

01:22:34.800 --> 01:22:40.980
temples apart were already at work. In
fact, in an ironic twist of fate, it would

01:22:40.980 --> 01:22:45.840
be the temples themselves that would
contribute to the gradual weakening and

01:22:45.840 --> 01:22:50.960
the eventual fall of this entire
civilization.

01:22:58.320 --> 01:23:03.600
Despite the efforts of King Anawrahta
to reign in the excessive power and

01:23:03.600 --> 01:23:08.760
wealth of the Ari monks, the Theravada
church that replaced them would soon

01:23:08.760 --> 01:23:14.520
become just as wealthy, and by the height
of Bagan's golden age, it would far

01:23:14.520 --> 01:23:19.679
surpass the wealth and power that its
predecessors had enjoyed.

01:23:19.679 --> 01:23:24.719
For the rulers of Bagan, the church was a
powerful tool for building their own

01:23:24.719 --> 01:23:30.659
legitimacy among their subjects.
The kings of Burma ruled under the title

01:23:30.659 --> 01:23:36.659
Dharma Raja, meaning a king who would
uphold the duties of the church.

01:23:36.659 --> 01:23:42.239
Whenever a new king was crowned, he would
begin his reign by lavishing gifts on

01:23:42.239 --> 01:23:47.640
nearby religious institutions, building
new temples and donating plots of land

01:23:47.640 --> 01:23:51.540
to the monks.
But it wasn't just the king who

01:23:51.540 --> 01:23:56.340
contributed to these institutions;
the church also encouraged private

01:23:56.340 --> 01:24:00.780
citizens to donate land and money in
exchange for benefits when they were

01:24:00.780 --> 01:24:06.719
reborn in the next life. One ancient
Burmese poem offers a starkly

01:24:06.719 --> 01:24:11.820
transactional approach to these
incentives, offering a kind of tiered

01:24:11.820 --> 01:24:15.320
system of rewards.

01:24:18.560 --> 01:24:24.060
He who gives and urges others to give
things in charity will be reborn rich,

01:24:24.060 --> 01:24:28.340
surrounded by numerous attendants, and
holding vast possessions.

01:24:28.340 --> 01:24:32.360
He will be a shining moon in the
assembly of men.

01:24:32.360 --> 01:24:37.920
He who earnestly encourages others to
give donations freely while himself

01:24:37.920 --> 01:24:44.520
offering nothing, in future rebirths will
be deficient in material belongings, yet

01:24:44.520 --> 01:24:51.020
many attendants and relatives, sons and
grandsons will be in his entourage.

01:24:51.020 --> 01:24:56.880
Whosoever neither himself is generous,
nor urges others to be, will encounter

01:24:56.880 --> 01:25:02.820
evil fate after his body's dissolution,
never feeling satiated, scarcely finding

01:25:02.820 --> 01:25:08.480
eating plants, showing hunger day and
night. He will become a hungry spirit,

01:25:08.480 --> 01:25:12.920
meeting all kinds of misery.

01:25:21.540 --> 01:25:26.159
With such punishments awaiting those who
refused to donate to the church in the

01:25:26.159 --> 01:25:33.560
next life, it's not hard to see why
people donated freely and generously.

01:25:37.260 --> 01:25:44.520
These donations of gold, goods, and labor
made the church incredibly wealthy, but

01:25:44.520 --> 01:25:49.500
it was the donations of land that really
tipped the balance in the kingdom.

01:25:49.500 --> 01:25:55.080
Anything given to the church was given
forever, and so as time went on, an

01:25:55.080 --> 01:25:59.639
increasingly large amount of the landmass
of Myanmar and much of its

01:25:59.639 --> 01:26:04.860
productive farmland was slowly donated
away piece by piece to the Buddhist

01:26:04.860 --> 01:26:08.340
church.
This wouldn't have been so much of a

01:26:08.340 --> 01:26:13.440
problem except for one thing; that's the
fact that according to a long-standing

01:26:13.440 --> 01:26:19.739
tradition, the Buddhist church in Bagan
was exempt from paying all taxes.

01:26:19.739 --> 01:26:26.580
This meant that these large temple
estates ended up acting like tax havens.

01:26:26.580 --> 01:26:32.219
Today the equivalent of 10% of the
world's wealth is held in tax havens,

01:26:32.219 --> 01:26:37.980
where the rich keep their money to avoid
paying tax on it. But in some modern

01:26:37.980 --> 01:26:43.679
states like Russia, several Latin
American countries like Argentina, and in

01:26:43.679 --> 01:26:48.659
the oil states of the Persian Gulf, the
amount of wealth held in offshore tax

01:26:48.659 --> 01:26:54.600
havens can exceed 60 percent.
A state's ability to function is

01:26:54.600 --> 01:26:59.340
directly linked to its ability to raise
funds and to marshal its collective

01:26:59.340 --> 01:27:04.620
resources for the public good.
Money taken into tax havens has

01:27:04.620 --> 01:27:09.659
effectively left the economy, and in
Myanmar between the 10th and the 13th

01:27:09.659 --> 01:27:14.219
centuries, the situation began to look
similar to some of the modern world's

01:27:14.219 --> 01:27:21.540
worst areas for tax evasion. In Bagan, by
the late 13th century, as much as 63

01:27:21.540 --> 01:27:26.219
percent of the kingdom's land that had
once belonged to the crown, as well as

01:27:26.219 --> 01:27:32.520
the majority of its gold and silver, was
in the hands of the tax-exempt church.

01:27:32.520 --> 01:27:38.219
For successive kings of Bagan, this
resulted in something of a bind.

01:27:38.219 --> 01:27:43.920
Their entire legitimacy rested on the
system of belief that began and ended

01:27:43.920 --> 01:27:48.719
with the Buddhist church, and so the
thought of using any kind of force to

01:27:48.719 --> 01:27:53.580
seize land from the unarmed Buddhist
monks was unthinkable.

01:27:53.580 --> 01:27:58.380
The church wasn't just a beloved
religious institution. It was also the

01:27:58.380 --> 01:28:02.219
land's biggest employer, and countless
people depended on it for their

01:28:02.219 --> 01:28:06.179
livelihood.
So, if the Burmese kings had any hope

01:28:06.179 --> 01:28:10.199
of getting their land back, they would
have to use the doctrines of the church

01:28:10.199 --> 01:28:13.100
against it.

01:28:15.900 --> 01:28:21.659
Buddhist doctrines in Burma did allow
for a sort of release valve on the power

01:28:21.659 --> 01:28:26.280
and influence of the church.
Monks were supposed to live by the

01:28:26.280 --> 01:28:32.100
Vinaya, or the Buddhist code of conduct,
which emphasizes relinquishing yourself

01:28:32.100 --> 01:28:36.840
of Earthly possessions,
and it was considered the duty of kings

01:28:36.840 --> 01:28:43.139
to periodically purge the church when it
wandered too far from this ideal. If the

01:28:43.139 --> 01:28:47.639
church had become too wealthy, then by
definition it must have strayed from the

01:28:47.639 --> 01:28:53.040
Vinaya, and so a process called Sasana
could begin.

01:28:53.040 --> 01:28:58.320
This was a kind of inquisition in which
individual temples were inspected and

01:28:58.320 --> 01:29:02.639
excess wealth or land could be
confiscated, according to a strict

01:29:02.639 --> 01:29:07.080
religious code.
It was a way for the crown to claw back

01:29:07.080 --> 01:29:10.500
some of the wealth it had lost to the
church,

01:29:10.500 --> 01:29:15.480
but the process of Sasana was slow and
often insufficient.

01:29:15.480 --> 01:29:20.940
Once a stage of Sasana purifying of the
church was finished, often the population

01:29:20.940 --> 01:29:27.120
felt newly inspired to donate to their
now pure and righteous church, and money

01:29:27.120 --> 01:29:31.800
would start flowing back to the monks in
even greater amounts.

01:29:31.800 --> 01:29:37.139
After a king had purified the church, his
descendants would often give even more

01:29:37.139 --> 01:29:42.060
lavish donations the moment they came to
the throne in order to increase their

01:29:42.060 --> 01:29:47.219
own legitimacy.
So, over the centuries, the wealth of

01:29:47.219 --> 01:29:52.920
the empire of Bagan flowed in only one
direction, from the great reservoir of

01:29:52.920 --> 01:29:57.900
the royal treasury downhill into the
tax-exempt sector of the religious

01:29:57.900 --> 01:30:03.960
establishment. The historian Michael
Aung-Thwin summarizes the situation in the

01:30:03.960 --> 01:30:09.719
following terms.
The kingdom of Bagan declined because

01:30:09.719 --> 01:30:16.020
the factors that had nurtured it in the
first place became in time forces that

01:30:16.020 --> 01:30:22.560
contradicted and destroyed it. The seeds
that sowed the destruction of Bagan are

01:30:22.560 --> 01:30:27.659
what earlier made its success possible,
and the institutions that led to

01:30:27.659 --> 01:30:34.500
prosperity and power eventually
involuted and impoverished the state.

01:30:34.500 --> 01:30:40.860
What had been a blessing became a curse.
But because Bagan society was unable and

01:30:40.860 --> 01:30:45.659
unwilling to change what were once
constructive forces when they became

01:30:45.659 --> 01:30:52.100
destructive ones, the political power of
the dynasty collapsed.

01:30:52.260 --> 01:30:59.040
By the reign of a king named Htilominlo,
who ruled in the early 13th century, it's

01:30:59.040 --> 01:31:04.260
clear that the royal treasury was
struggling. He was the last king of Bagan

01:31:04.260 --> 01:31:09.420
to build any significant temples,
although he did so mostly in remote

01:31:09.420 --> 01:31:14.460
regions away from the capital.
The kings who followed would be

01:31:14.460 --> 01:31:19.139
apparently penniless, and no great
constructions would go up after this

01:31:19.139 --> 01:31:21.560
period.

01:31:26.880 --> 01:31:31.440
When discussing the collapse of
societies, historians often talk about

01:31:31.440 --> 01:31:35.580
what they call the remote origins of the
collapse.

01:31:35.580 --> 01:31:41.639
These are slow, broad trends that build
up over time, cracks that begin to appear

01:31:41.639 --> 01:31:47.219
and wear away at the structure, sometimes
invisible, and then there's what they

01:31:47.219 --> 01:31:53.340
call the immediate origins. This is the
wrecking ball that comes swinging in and

01:31:53.340 --> 01:31:57.540
delivers one decisive blow that
reverberates through the cracked and

01:31:57.540 --> 01:32:02.880
weakened structure and sends the whole
thing shattering into smithereens.

01:32:02.880 --> 01:32:08.820
The state of Bagan’s reduced ability to
Marshal its land and resources was not

01:32:08.820 --> 01:32:13.380
fatal by itself, but it left it
increasingly vulnerable to outside

01:32:13.380 --> 01:32:18.360
events.
In the year 1258, a series of rebellions

01:32:18.360 --> 01:32:24.960
began in South Arakan and Martaban, and
posed a challenge to the empire.

01:32:24.960 --> 01:32:30.179
With as much as two-thirds of its land
held by the church, the Bagan state

01:32:30.179 --> 01:32:35.760
struggled to fund the military campaign
necessary to contain these rebellions.

01:32:35.760 --> 01:32:40.020
Though it would ultimately bring order
back to those regions after a struggle

01:32:40.020 --> 01:32:46.080
of many years, it was a clear indication
of the weakened state of the country.

01:32:46.080 --> 01:32:50.820
But soon, an even more terrible threat
began to loom.

01:32:50.820 --> 01:32:55.800
This was a force of the size and
strength that the people of Bagan had

01:32:55.800 --> 01:33:00.840
never encountered before, a force that
even now was sweeping across the

01:33:00.840 --> 01:33:06.780
Eurasian landmass, washing away empires
that had ruled for centuries, and leaving

01:33:06.780 --> 01:33:13.020
death and destruction in its wake.
These were the armies of the Mongol

01:33:13.020 --> 01:33:17.000
emperor Kublai Khan.

01:33:27.120 --> 01:33:34.020
Kublai Khan was a grandson of the great
Mongol warlord Genghis Khan, who had

01:33:34.020 --> 01:33:39.360
united the steppe peoples of Mongolia and
led them on a campaign of conquest the

01:33:39.360 --> 01:33:44.159
likes of which the world had never seen,
conquering lands from the South China

01:33:44.159 --> 01:33:50.159
Sea to the Mediterranean, from Siberia to
Afghanistan.

01:33:50.159 --> 01:33:56.219
Kublai was 12 years old when his
grandfather Genghis Khan died, and after

01:33:56.219 --> 01:34:01.139
the death of the great Khan, the vast
Mongol empire began to split into

01:34:01.139 --> 01:34:06.540
warring rival states.
Kublai Khan would find himself at the

01:34:06.540 --> 01:34:11.460
head of the Chinese portion of the
Mongol Empire, and founded a dynasty

01:34:11.460 --> 01:34:16.620
known as the Yuan, with his capital at
Beijing.

01:34:16.620 --> 01:34:22.380
In just three generations, the Mongols
had gone from nomadic wanderers to

01:34:22.380 --> 01:34:27.840
emperors, and over time, the Yuan Dynasty
would come to rule over most of

01:34:27.840 --> 01:34:33.300
present-day China, Mongolia, Korea, and
Southern Siberia.

01:34:33.300 --> 01:34:38.580
In the late 13th century, at the same
time that the Bagan Empire was

01:34:38.580 --> 01:34:43.560
struggling to contain its rebellious
northern provinces and claw back some of

01:34:43.560 --> 01:34:49.380
its land and wealth from its church, the
emperor Kublai Khan was engaged in an

01:34:49.380 --> 01:34:55.080
immense war against his last remaining
rivals in China. These were the Southern

01:34:55.080 --> 01:35:01.500
Song Dynasty, a large Chinese kingdom
that had until now resisted the advances

01:35:01.500 --> 01:35:06.600
of the Mongols.
But by the year 1270, the Song were on

01:35:06.600 --> 01:35:11.159
the ropes.
Kublai Khan had blockaded the Yangtze

01:35:11.159 --> 01:35:16.380
River, cutting off their supply routes,
and he was now keen to encircle and

01:35:16.380 --> 01:35:21.900
destroy any remaining Song armies.
But he had one problem;

01:35:21.900 --> 01:35:26.699
there was still a single remaining
escape route for the Song armies, and

01:35:26.699 --> 01:35:31.199
that was through the narrow mountain
passes in the southwest of China and

01:35:31.199 --> 01:35:35.880
into the lands of Myanmar.
If the Song armies were able to escape

01:35:35.880 --> 01:35:39.960
through the lands of Bagan, they could
continue their fight.

01:35:39.960 --> 01:35:46.199
So, Kublai Khan resolved to bring the
empire of Bagan under his sway and close

01:35:46.199 --> 01:35:52.620
off the Song's final escape route.
With his forces all tied up in total war

01:35:52.620 --> 01:35:58.560
against the Song, Kublai at first had no
desire for conflict with Bagan.

01:35:58.560 --> 01:36:04.020
He sent an envoy to the Burmese court
and demanded that the king there swear

01:36:04.020 --> 01:36:11.219
loyalty to him and pay a small tribute.
As Mongol tactics went, this was about as

01:36:11.219 --> 01:36:15.900
polite as you could get.
But things would not go according to his

01:36:15.900 --> 01:36:18.199
plan.

01:36:20.580 --> 01:36:26.460
The king of Bagan at this time was a man
named Narathihapate.

01:36:26.460 --> 01:36:32.699
He was a man of overwhelming appetites,
who loved his food and drink so much so

01:36:32.699 --> 01:36:38.040
that the Glass Palace Chronicle records
that he was the reincarnation of an ogre

01:36:38.040 --> 01:36:44.460
who lived on Mount Popa.
The Lord had left a prophecy upon the

01:36:44.460 --> 01:36:49.440
top of Mount Tangvi that the ogre,
guardian of the mountain, should become

01:36:49.440 --> 01:36:55.500
king thrice in Bagan.
Even so, it came to pass, for he became

01:36:55.500 --> 01:37:02.100
king once, it is said, as Narathihapate,
and because he had become a man from the

01:37:02.100 --> 01:37:08.460
state of an ogre, he was violent in envy,
proud and wrathful, and gluttonous in

01:37:08.460 --> 01:37:13.380
eating and drinking.
He was great in wrath, haughtiness, and

01:37:13.380 --> 01:37:20.460
envy, exceeding covetous and ambitious. He
had three thousand concubines and maids

01:37:20.460 --> 01:37:22.880
of honor.

01:37:23.040 --> 01:37:28.620
If the chronicles are to be believed,
this King Narathihapate also ruled

01:37:28.620 --> 01:37:33.420
tyrannically, with some of his
preoccupations ranging into the

01:37:33.420 --> 01:37:38.940
territory of the bizarre.
The king, being one who had received the

01:37:38.940 --> 01:37:44.699
Lord's prophecy, suffered not from any of
the 96 diseases, and never so much has

01:37:44.699 --> 01:37:50.400
sneezed nor yawned. So, none was
allowed to sneeze or yawn in his

01:37:50.400 --> 01:37:55.560
presence. If anyone happened to sneeze or
yawn, he beheaded him.

01:37:55.560 --> 01:38:00.540
One day, a young handmaid in the king's
presence was dearly desired to sneeze,

01:38:00.540 --> 01:38:05.760
and because she could not refrain it she
put her face to a great jar and sneezed,

01:38:05.760 --> 01:38:11.400
hoping that the king would not hear, but
alas, the sound was louder than if she

01:38:11.400 --> 01:38:17.699
had sneezed openly, and the king asked,
‘What sound is that?’

01:38:17.699 --> 01:38:21.900
It's only through the gentle
intervention of one of his queens that

01:38:21.900 --> 01:38:27.260
the unfortunate girl was allowed to
escape with her life. King Narathihapate

01:38:27.560 --> 01:38:33.420
was also given over to boasting,
especially about his famous appetite, as

01:38:33.420 --> 01:38:41.219
one inscription left by him at the
Mingalar Zedi Pagoda in 1274 shows.

01:38:41.219 --> 01:38:49.080
King Narathihapate, supreme commander of
36 million soldiers and who is the

01:38:49.080 --> 01:38:56.940
consumer of 300 dishes of curry daily,
enshrined 51 gold and silver figurines

01:38:56.940 --> 01:39:03.360
of kings, queens, nobles, and maids of
honor, on Thursday the full moon of

01:39:03.360 --> 01:39:11.219
Kason of the year 636.
So, in January of the year 1271, a

01:39:11.219 --> 01:39:17.100
group of ambassadors arrived in Bagan
from the court of Kublai Khan in Beijing,

01:39:17.100 --> 01:39:23.100
with the Mongol emperor's offer.
These ambassadors asked to see the

01:39:23.100 --> 01:39:28.020
Burmese king Narathihapate, and when they
were let into the throne room, they

01:39:28.020 --> 01:39:32.940
demanded that the king submit to being a
vassal of the Mongols.

01:39:32.940 --> 01:39:38.699
This ogre-like king refused.
The Glass Palace Chronicle remembers

01:39:38.699 --> 01:39:45.000
this encounter in dramatic terms, and
uses the Burmese name Taruk or Turk to

01:39:45.000 --> 01:39:50.940
describe the Mongol ambassador.
The Taruk sent 10 ministers and a

01:39:50.940 --> 01:39:56.460
thousand horsemen to demand golden
ricepots, vessels of gold and silver, gold and

01:39:56.460 --> 01:40:03.719
silver ladles, because, said he, they were
once offered by King Anawrahta.

01:40:03.719 --> 01:40:09.120
Furthermore, some chronicles say that
they came demanding a white elephant.

01:40:09.120 --> 01:40:14.760
The Taruk ambassadors in making demands
showed no due respect nor reverence in

01:40:14.760 --> 01:40:19.739
the king's presence.
Therefore, the king commanded,

01:40:19.739 --> 01:40:25.920
slay these 10 ministers and thousand
horsemen. Let none escape.

01:40:25.920 --> 01:40:32.040
Both Burmese and Mongol inscriptions of
the time indicate that this sentence was

01:40:32.040 --> 01:40:37.020
not actually carried out, with the king's
advisors perhaps pleading with him to be

01:40:37.020 --> 01:40:42.300
rational. But it shows the extent to
which the Mongol demands angered this

01:40:42.300 --> 01:40:45.480
King Narathihapate.

01:40:45.600 --> 01:40:51.060
Back in Beijing, we can only imagine the
scenes as Kublai Khan was informed of

01:40:51.060 --> 01:40:55.440
this insult.
But he was still reluctant to order an

01:40:55.440 --> 01:41:00.000
invasion. He was battling the last
remnants of the Song Dynasty in the

01:41:00.000 --> 01:41:05.060
south, and he had just attempted an
ill-fated sea invasion of Japan,

01:41:05.060 --> 01:41:09.420
capturing the island of Tsushima, and
attempting to land on the Japanese

01:41:09.420 --> 01:41:14.940
mainland. But his ships had been
destroyed in a pair of typhoons that the

01:41:14.940 --> 01:41:20.820
Japanese would later name the Divine
Winds or Kamikaze, and ten thousand

01:41:20.820 --> 01:41:27.300
Mongol soldiers had been lost.
After this embarrassment, Kublai Khan had

01:41:27.300 --> 01:41:32.760
no great desire to commit a large number
of troops to a small border dispute with

01:41:32.760 --> 01:41:37.139
Bagan.
Instead he ordered his armies to move

01:41:37.139 --> 01:41:42.000
into a wide swathe of contested
borderlands in the forbidding mountain

01:41:42.000 --> 01:41:49.199
ranges between his empire and Burma.
In response, the king of Bagan refused to

01:41:49.199 --> 01:41:54.780
back down, and sent his own armies to
recapture the region, backed by a large

01:41:54.780 --> 01:41:58.340
force of war elephants.

01:41:58.980 --> 01:42:04.320
This Burmese army marched up into the
thickly forested hills.

01:42:04.320 --> 01:42:09.179
We can only imagine how the soldiers
felt marching to war with this unknown

01:42:09.179 --> 01:42:14.040
enemy, of which they must have heard
terrifying tales.

01:42:14.040 --> 01:42:19.920
One Burmese poet writing later would
give a description of an army marching

01:42:19.920 --> 01:42:22.400
to battle.

01:42:26.060 --> 01:42:32.520
We are not afraid of anything. We are
daring and brave, ready to sacrifice our

01:42:32.520 --> 01:42:40.500
lives, marching to the Royal City. On this
day, fixed as the Day of Victory, at our

01:42:40.500 --> 01:42:47.159
camp in the forest verdant, are the
branches full of small flower buds. Sweet

01:42:47.159 --> 01:42:54.179
are the sounds of the military drums and
gongs in the soft evening twilight. Just

01:42:54.179 --> 01:43:02.060
as mists and clouds are dispersed, so too
must we destroy our enemy.

01:43:04.139 --> 01:43:09.239
This army finally met the Mongol
garrison at a rocky forested gully

01:43:09.239 --> 01:43:15.960
known as the Vochang Valley.
The explorer and adventurer Marco Polo

01:43:15.960 --> 01:43:21.780
by this time was serving as a diplomat
in the court of Kublai Khan. He recalls

01:43:21.780 --> 01:43:28.980
the force that the king of Bagan sent.
So, this king prepared a great force and

01:43:28.980 --> 01:43:35.820
munitions of war and he had, let me tell
you, two thousand great elephants, on each

01:43:35.820 --> 01:43:41.760
of which was set a tower of timber, well
framed and strong, and carrying from 12

01:43:41.760 --> 01:43:48.480
to 16 well-armed fighting men.
Besides these, he had of horsemen and

01:43:48.480 --> 01:43:56.520
of footmen good 60,000 men. In short, he
equipped a fine force as well befitted

01:43:56.520 --> 01:44:03.000
such a powerful prince. It was indeed a
host capable of doing great things,

01:44:03.000 --> 01:44:06.960
and what shall I tell you when the king
had completed these great preparations

01:44:06.960 --> 01:44:12.900
to fight the Tartars, he tarried not. They
arrived within three days of the great

01:44:12.900 --> 01:44:19.080
Khan's host, which was then at Vochan, in
the territory of Zardandan.

01:44:19.080 --> 01:44:23.820
It's likely that for many of the Mongol
soldiers, this was their first experience

01:44:23.820 --> 01:44:29.820
of seeing war elephants fielded in
combat. These enormous creatures would

01:44:29.820 --> 01:44:34.619
have advanced in a terrifying wall, with
their wooden superstructures carrying

01:44:34.619 --> 01:44:40.440
archers. Marco Polo describes what
happened next.

01:44:40.440 --> 01:44:45.179
When the king's army had arrived in the
plain and was within a mile of the enemy,

01:44:45.179 --> 01:44:49.139
he caused all the castles that were on
the elephants to be ordered for battle,

01:44:49.139 --> 01:44:53.460
and the fighting men to take up their
posts on them, and he arrayed his horse

01:44:53.460 --> 01:44:58.380
and his foot. The horses of the Tartars
took such fright at the sight of the

01:44:58.380 --> 01:45:02.699
elephants that they could not be got to
face the foe, but always swerved and

01:45:02.699 --> 01:45:07.880
turned back, whilst all the time the king
and his forces and all his elephants

01:45:07.880 --> 01:45:12.900
continued to advance upon them.
But the Mongols had learned their

01:45:12.900 --> 01:45:18.239
tactics on the vast open steppes of
Central Asia, and they knew that when an

01:45:18.239 --> 01:45:23.219
enemy was too strong to face directly,
you could always retreat and pepper them

01:45:23.219 --> 01:45:28.500
with arrows from a distance, and that's
exactly what they did.

01:45:28.500 --> 01:45:33.960
When the Tartars perceived how the case
stood, they were in great wrath and knew

01:45:33.960 --> 01:45:39.540
not what to say or do, but their captain
acted like a wise leader who had

01:45:39.540 --> 01:45:45.179
considered everything beforehand. They
did as he bade them, and plied their

01:45:45.179 --> 01:45:50.340
bow stoutly, shooting so many shafts at
the advancing elephants that in a short

01:45:50.340 --> 01:45:55.679
space they had wounded or slain the
greater part of them, as well as of the

01:45:55.679 --> 01:46:00.719
men they carried. When the elephants felt
the smart of those arrows that pelted

01:46:00.719 --> 01:46:06.960
them like rain, they turned tail and fled,
and nothing on Earth would have induced

01:46:06.960 --> 01:46:11.940
them to turn and face the Tartars.
Then, too, they plunged into the wood and

01:46:11.940 --> 01:46:17.340
rushed this way and that, dashing their
castles against the trees, bursting their

01:46:17.340 --> 01:46:25.040
harness, and smashing and destroying
everything that was on them.

01:46:26.460 --> 01:46:31.440
With the enemy in disarray, the Mongol
cavalry charged down on them and the

01:46:31.440 --> 01:46:38.040
forces of Bagan were scattered.
The Mongol chronicles can barely conceal

01:46:38.040 --> 01:46:44.100
their pride at the size of this victory.
They record that only 700 Mongol

01:46:44.100 --> 01:46:51.000
soldiers were able to defeat a Burmese
army of 50,000 while only losing a

01:46:51.000 --> 01:46:56.340
single soldier, but this is clearly an
exaggeration. The Burmese chronicles,

01:46:56.340 --> 01:47:01.980
perhaps understandably, make no mention
of this disastrous campaign.

01:47:01.980 --> 01:47:07.440
The main force of Bagan had been utterly
defeated on what should have been their

01:47:07.440 --> 01:47:12.900
home turf, and there was now little
standing between the Mongol armies and

01:47:12.900 --> 01:47:17.300
the rich river valley of the Irrawaddy.

01:47:17.580 --> 01:47:21.840
The Mongols were quick to capitalize on
their victory.

01:47:21.840 --> 01:47:28.260
Kaungsin, the next fort along the road,
fell just six days later, on the 9th of

01:47:28.260 --> 01:47:36.239
December 1283, and now the Mongol forces
pushed on into the Irrawaddy valley.

01:47:36.239 --> 01:47:41.760
It's clear from the exaggerated tones of
the Burmese Chronicles just how much of

01:47:41.760 --> 01:47:48.300
a threat this Mongol invasion force was.
The Turk mustered all the parts of his army

01:47:48.300 --> 01:47:52.800
to the number of 6 million horsemen
and 20 million footmen,

01:47:52.800 --> 01:48:00.080
and they came marching.
The situation clearly looked bleak. King

01:48:00.080 --> 01:48:05.659
Narathihapate ordered two of his generals to take
his remaining forces and fortify the town of

01:48:05.659 --> 01:48:11.100
Ngahsaunggyan on the crucial river
crossing of the Irrawaddy.

01:48:11.100 --> 01:48:18.600
Coming to Ngahsaunggyan town, they made
it strong and girded it with forts and

01:48:18.600 --> 01:48:24.600
moats and ditches, and fought in their
defense at the river crossing of Bhamo.

01:48:24.600 --> 01:48:30.840
For three full months they slew the
enemy and spared not even the feeders of

01:48:30.840 --> 01:48:38.280
elephants and horses, but slew them all.
But when 10 myriad men were dead, the

01:48:38.280 --> 01:48:46.199
Taruk sent 20 myriad. When 20 myriad
were dead, he sent 40 myriad. The king's

01:48:46.199 --> 01:48:53.280
men were weary and fore-done, and as soon
as the Taruks crossed the river,

01:48:53.280 --> 01:48:56.300
Ngahsaunggyan fell.

01:48:57.060 --> 01:49:04.380
At the news of the fall of Ngahsaunggyan,
the ogre-like king's courage failed him.

01:49:04.380 --> 01:49:09.540
He fled the city of Bagan and headed to
the south.

01:49:09.540 --> 01:49:17.219
Then the king called his ministers and
consulted with them, saying Bagan town is

01:49:17.219 --> 01:49:21.480
now too narrow for us, in depth too
shallow.

01:49:21.480 --> 01:49:27.179
It cannot contain the hosts of fighting
men, the hosts of elephants and horses.

01:49:27.179 --> 01:49:34.619
Let us go straight away to the south and
establish a strong town.

01:49:34.619 --> 01:49:36.800
For this reason, King Narathihapate

01:49:39.739 --> 01:49:46.679
would go down in history in Burma by the
name Taruk-Pye Min, or the king who fled

01:49:46.679 --> 01:49:52.199
from the Turks.
He retreated into the south of Burma and

01:49:52.199 --> 01:49:56.520
left the rest of the country leaderless
and in chaos.

01:49:56.520 --> 01:50:01.440
With no remaining confidence in the king
of Bagan to protect them, many of the

01:50:01.440 --> 01:50:07.739
empire's provinces simply broke away and
looked to their own defenses.

01:50:07.739 --> 01:50:13.020
For the next year, the king attempted to
negotiate with the Mongol invaders, and

01:50:13.020 --> 01:50:18.119
throughout this time, the lowlands of
Burma were a battlefield convulsed in a

01:50:18.119 --> 01:50:24.119
series of constant running skirmishes.
It's not actually certain whether or not

01:50:24.119 --> 01:50:28.860
the Mongol forces reached the capital
city of Bagan.

01:50:28.860 --> 01:50:32.820
According to Burmese sources, the
generals that the king had sent to

01:50:32.820 --> 01:50:37.440
defend the north seemed to have been
able to slow the Mongol advance and even

01:50:37.440 --> 01:50:42.239
repel them about 160 kilometers north of
the capital.

01:50:42.239 --> 01:50:48.000
Some sources claim quite plausibly that
the Mongol soldiers struggled in the

01:50:48.000 --> 01:50:52.980
baking heat of Myanmar's Dry Zone and
suffered from diseases like malaria,

01:50:52.980 --> 01:50:57.000
which sapped the momentum out of their
campaign.

01:50:57.000 --> 01:51:02.340
Archeology seems to support this story,
since on the temples and structures of

01:51:02.340 --> 01:51:07.320
Bagan, there's little evidence of war
damage or burning.

01:51:07.320 --> 01:51:13.380
Marco Polo, in the court of Kublai Khan,
claims that the Mongols did reach Bagan,

01:51:13.380 --> 01:51:18.659
but explains that they left the temples
intact out of some mixture of respect

01:51:18.659 --> 01:51:21.920
and superstition.

01:51:22.619 --> 01:51:27.659
They marched until they came to the
country and province of Mien, and they

01:51:27.659 --> 01:51:32.280
did conquer the whole of it, and when
they found in the city the two towers of

01:51:32.280 --> 01:51:36.780
gold and silver, they were greatly
astonished and sent word thereof to the

01:51:36.780 --> 01:51:41.580
great Khan, asking what he would have
them do with the two towers,

01:51:41.580 --> 01:51:45.360
seeing what a great quantity of wealth
there was upon them.

01:51:45.360 --> 01:51:50.880
The great Khan, being well aware that
the king had caused these towers to be

01:51:50.880 --> 01:51:55.560
made for the good of his soul and to
preserve his memory after his death, said

01:51:55.560 --> 01:52:00.360
that he would not have them injured but
would have them left precisely as they

01:52:00.360 --> 01:52:05.400
were, and that was no wonder either, for
ye must know that no Tartar in the world

01:52:05.400 --> 01:52:12.440
will ever, if he can help it, lay hand on
anything appertaining to the dead.

01:52:13.460 --> 01:52:19.980
Whatever the situation, the Mongols had
no interest in a drawn-out conflict.

01:52:19.980 --> 01:52:25.860
By the year 1287, the Mongol Khan had
agreed to a tentative peace.

01:52:25.860 --> 01:52:30.659
The Burmese delegation formally
acknowledged Mongol power over their

01:52:30.659 --> 01:52:34.679
kingdom and agreed to pay an annual
tribute that was a certain proportion

01:52:34.679 --> 01:52:38.699
of the annual agricultural output of the
country.

01:52:38.699 --> 01:52:42.840
But the agreement broke down only a
month later.

01:52:42.840 --> 01:52:48.780
In late June, the defeated and humiliated
King Narathihapate was returning from

01:52:48.780 --> 01:52:53.699
the south, traveling north up the river
on his royal barge to take up his

01:52:53.699 --> 01:52:59.460
position as a puppet king in the capital
he had fled years before. But on

01:52:59.460 --> 01:53:06.960
the 1st of July, 1287, King Narathihapate
was intercepted en route by his

01:53:06.960 --> 01:53:12.719
second son Thihathu, who had him
assassinated.

01:53:12.719 --> 01:53:17.219
They went upstream in route and disarray
without union or order,

01:53:17.219 --> 01:53:21.780
and when they reached the port of
Promay, Thihathu stopped the royal raft

01:53:21.780 --> 01:53:28.080
and put poison in the food.
He offered it and said O King, eat,

01:53:28.080 --> 01:53:32.940
but the king knew that there was poison
in the food and he would not eat. When

01:53:32.940 --> 01:53:37.260
Thihathu heard he had caused three
thousand soldiers to go and stand around

01:53:37.260 --> 01:53:41.400
the royal raft with gleaming swords
unsheathed within their hands,

01:53:41.400 --> 01:53:47.639
then he took the ring off his finger and
he let four drops of water over it, and

01:53:47.639 --> 01:53:52.199
gave it to his queen.
And he made a solemn vow and said,

01:53:52.199 --> 01:53:57.239
‘In all the lives we're in, I wander
throughout Samsara until I reach

01:53:57.239 --> 01:54:02.760
nirvana. May I never have a son born to
me again,’ and he took the food and ate,

01:54:02.760 --> 01:54:08.119
and even as he ate, he died.

01:54:10.739 --> 01:54:15.239
The death of this king was the final
death blow for the disintegrating

01:54:15.239 --> 01:54:20.280
kingdom of Bagan.
All remaining provinces that had once

01:54:20.280 --> 01:54:25.380
been loyal to it now broke away.
There was no king at all for the next

01:54:25.380 --> 01:54:32.280
two years, and when one of Narathihapate’s
sons, named Kyawswa, did emerge as ruler, he

01:54:32.280 --> 01:54:38.219
would reign over only the diminished and
impoverished city of Bagan itself, and he

01:54:38.219 --> 01:54:43.260
had virtually no army.
He would be assassinated along with his

01:54:43.260 --> 01:54:48.719
son and heir on the 10th of May, 1299.

01:54:53.580 --> 01:54:59.100
It was during this time that the
explorer Marco Polo visited the city of

01:54:59.100 --> 01:55:04.800
Bagan and saw with his own eyes the
glorious sights of its temples now

01:55:04.800 --> 01:55:11.580
diminished by the years of war.
Throughout this whole period, the Mongols

01:55:11.580 --> 01:55:16.980
could have easily moved in to occupy the
territory of Bagan, but it seems they had

01:55:16.980 --> 01:55:22.739
no interest in doing so. In fact, they
would send no more expeditions to

01:55:22.739 --> 01:55:27.540
restore order.
Their policy seems to have been to allow

01:55:27.540 --> 01:55:32.580
the fragmentation of the kingdom to
continue, and to watch from afar as the

01:55:32.580 --> 01:55:37.679
once great power that had challenged
them simply tore itself apart and sank

01:55:37.679 --> 01:55:40.820
into irrelevance.

01:55:41.639 --> 01:55:48.300
One 14th century king named Mingyi
Swasawke wrote a later inscription with

01:55:48.300 --> 01:55:56.340
a brief sad note about this time.
The Burmese Empire disintegrated because

01:55:56.340 --> 01:56:02.040
of internal strife.
The collapse of the empire of

01:56:02.040 --> 01:56:06.260
Bagan was now complete.

01:56:11.460 --> 01:56:16.860
The area of the city of Bagan would
remain occupied for much of the century

01:56:16.860 --> 01:56:21.659
that followed, and people would continue
to farm and keep animals in the lands

01:56:21.659 --> 01:56:26.639
around the great temples and stupas as
they slowly crumbled beneath the forces

01:56:26.639 --> 01:56:32.280
of the elements.
Other kingdoms would occupy this region

01:56:32.280 --> 01:56:37.500
over time, some kings even crowning
themselves at Bagan and giving

01:56:37.500 --> 01:56:42.360
themselves the titles of the old
emperors, but the city would never again

01:56:42.360 --> 01:56:47.280
hold the same prominence.
A smaller number of new and impressive

01:56:47.280 --> 01:56:51.780
religious monuments still went up to the
mid 15th century,

01:56:51.780 --> 01:56:57.300
but after that, new temple constructions
slowed to a trickle and then stopped

01:56:57.300 --> 01:57:04.159
entirely,
and bit by bit, the city fell into ruin.

01:57:06.540 --> 01:57:13.380
The area of the city of Bagan remained a
pilgrimage site up until the modern day.

01:57:13.380 --> 01:57:17.880
While farmers grazed their cattle on the
grasses pushing up through the bricks,

01:57:17.880 --> 01:57:23.580
pilgrims traveled for hundreds of miles
to visit its unique landscape and see

01:57:23.580 --> 01:57:29.940
the awe-inspiring sight of its golden
domes and spires rising out of the

01:57:29.940 --> 01:57:35.219
morning mist of the flat river valley.
Some of the larger and more impressive

01:57:35.219 --> 01:57:40.739
temples would even be maintained and
repaired for centuries to come, but

01:57:40.739 --> 01:57:45.840
thousands of the less famous and more
out of the way temples fell into

01:57:45.840 --> 01:57:52.400
disrepair and ruin, some disappearing
entirely, crumbling into ruined mounds,

01:57:52.400 --> 01:57:56.780
swallowed up by the forests.

01:58:04.699 --> 01:58:10.440
The English writer William Somerset
Maugham who traveled through Burma and

01:58:10.440 --> 01:58:17.400
Thailand in 1923, wrote a memoir of his
travels entitled A Gentleman in the

01:58:17.400 --> 01:58:20.760
Parlor.
In it he writes about how he was

01:58:20.760 --> 01:58:26.099
affected by the sight of the ruins of
cities like Angkor,

01:58:26.099 --> 01:58:31.679
Ayuthaya, and Bagan.
In these Eastern countries, cities are

01:58:31.679 --> 01:58:37.260
founded, increased to greatness, and are
destroyed in a manner that cannot but

01:58:37.260 --> 01:58:42.420
fill the Western traveler, accustomed for
many centuries now to a relative

01:58:42.420 --> 01:58:48.719
stability, with a certain misgiving.
Here and there in the jungle, far from

01:58:48.719 --> 01:58:55.500
any habitation, you will find ruined
temples overgrown with trees, and among

01:58:55.500 --> 01:59:01.440
the dank verger, broken gods, and
elaborate bass reliefs as the only sign

01:59:01.440 --> 01:59:06.960
that here was once a thriving city, and
you will come across poverty-stricken

01:59:06.960 --> 01:59:13.260
villages that are all that remain of the
capital of a rich and powerful kingdom.

01:59:13.260 --> 01:59:19.760
It is a somber reminding of the
mutability of human things.

01:59:20.400 --> 01:59:25.619
For Maugham, the sight of these ruins
reminded him that the empire he lived at

01:59:25.619 --> 01:59:31.800
the heart of might also one day be
consigned to history.

01:59:31.800 --> 01:59:38.159
Maugham writes evocatively of his first
visit to the ruined temples of Bagan, as

01:59:38.159 --> 01:59:43.380
he approached by steamboat along the
great river Irrawaddy.

01:59:43.380 --> 01:59:49.380
A light rain was falling and the sky was
dark with heavy clouds when I reached

01:59:49.380 --> 01:59:55.440
Bagan. In the distance I saw the pagodas
for which it is renowned. They loomed

01:59:55.440 --> 02:00:01.560
huge, remote, and mysterious out of the
mist of the early morning like the vague

02:00:01.560 --> 02:00:07.380
recollections of a fantastic dream. I do
not know how many pagodas there are at

02:00:07.380 --> 02:00:13.199
Bagan. When you stand on an eminence, they
surround you for as far as the eye can

02:00:13.199 --> 02:00:18.540
reach. They are almost as thickly strewn
as the tombstones in a cemetery. They are

02:00:18.540 --> 02:00:24.780
of all sizes and in all states of
preservation. Their solidity and size and

02:00:24.780 --> 02:00:30.119
magnificence are the more striking by
reason of their surroundings, for they

02:00:30.119 --> 02:00:36.179
alone remain to show that here a vast
and populous city once flourished. Today

02:00:36.179 --> 02:00:41.880
there is only a straggling village with
broad untidy roads lined with great

02:00:41.880 --> 02:00:48.719
trees, a pleasant enough little place.
Over the next few days, Maugham would explore

02:00:48.719 --> 02:00:54.000
the crumbling ruins of these temples and
pagodas and walk among the dilapidated

02:00:54.000 --> 02:00:57.420
buildings,
and everywhere he found the place

02:00:57.420 --> 02:01:02.880
infused with a strange and lingering
melancholy.

02:01:02.880 --> 02:01:08.820
Within the pagodas, images of the Buddha
sit in meditation.

02:01:08.820 --> 02:01:14.639
The goldleaf has long since worn away
from the colossal figures, and the

02:01:14.639 --> 02:01:20.340
figures are crumbling to dust.
The fantastic lions that guard the

02:01:20.340 --> 02:01:26.760
entranceways are rotting on their
pedestals, a strange and melancholy spot.

02:01:26.760 --> 02:01:32.460
Grass grows in the chinks of the
pavement, and young trees have taken root

02:01:32.460 --> 02:01:37.260
in the crannies.
They are the refuge of birds.

02:01:37.260 --> 02:01:43.020
Hawks wheel about their summits and
little green parrots chatter in the

02:01:43.020 --> 02:01:46.440
eaves.
The birds were singing noisily in the

02:01:46.440 --> 02:01:52.679
trees. The crickets chirped and the frogs
croaked, croaked, croaked.

02:01:52.679 --> 02:01:58.340
Somewhere, a boy was whistling a
melancholy tune.

02:02:01.679 --> 02:02:06.239
I'd like to end the episode with a
reading from one of the great poets of

02:02:06.239 --> 02:02:11.280
the Bagan period, a man named
Anantasuriya.

02:02:11.280 --> 02:02:16.380
Anantasuriya was a scholar who served as
the chief minister in the kingdom of

02:02:16.380 --> 02:02:22.679
Bagan under King Naratheinka, who ruled in
the latter half of the 12th century.

02:02:22.679 --> 02:02:28.260
As a result of a palace coup, the king's
brother seized the throne and began

02:02:28.260 --> 02:02:33.840
purging the government of those loyal to
the previous king. Because of this,

02:02:33.840 --> 02:02:39.780
Anantasuriya was ordered to be executed,
and just like Marco Polo sitting in his

02:02:39.780 --> 02:02:46.320
jail cell in Genoa a century later on
the other side of the world, Anantasuriya

02:02:46.320 --> 02:02:51.119
turned in his time of imprisonment to
writing.

02:02:51.119 --> 02:02:56.159
While he sat in prison awaiting his
death, he wrote the following poem, which

02:02:56.159 --> 02:02:59.880
has gone down in history as one of the
most beautiful pieces of writing

02:02:59.880 --> 02:03:05.460
produced during the efflorescence of art
and culture that took place during the

02:03:05.460 --> 02:03:10.020
empire of Bagan.
It's a poem of loss and forgiveness,

02:03:10.020 --> 02:03:17.159
about ultimately accepting the fate of
all things to pass into darkness and

02:03:17.159 --> 02:03:21.300
dust.
As you listen, imagine what it would feel

02:03:21.300 --> 02:03:26.880
like to walk the emptying streets of the
city of Bagan as its temples crumbled

02:03:26.880 --> 02:03:33.060
and grasses grew up through its streets
and homes. Imagine watching trees push

02:03:33.060 --> 02:03:38.880
through the bricks of the temple stupas
and shaded doorways, animals running wild

02:03:38.880 --> 02:03:45.239
in the streets while the sun set in a
red haze over the hills and and the

02:03:45.239 --> 02:03:49.760
poets sang of the end of days.

02:03:56.300 --> 02:04:03.420
Often when one man prospers, another must
suffer destruction. Such is the nature of

02:04:03.420 --> 02:04:07.020
things.
A courtier's satisfaction in enjoying

02:04:07.020 --> 02:04:12.540
kingly confidences in golden palaces and
a king's own good fortune are merely

02:04:12.540 --> 02:04:19.380
bubbles on the surface of a vast ocean,
momentary and evanescent.

02:04:19.380 --> 02:04:26.060
If dictated by mercy and pity I were to
be released and freed from execution,

02:04:26.060 --> 02:04:31.800
still I would not escape death.
Inseparable am I from karma.

02:04:31.800 --> 02:04:35.960
It is the nature of every living thing
to decay.

02:04:35.960 --> 02:04:41.460
Should I again meet my lord the king in
one of my future rebirths in the cycle

02:04:41.460 --> 02:04:48.540
of Samsara, begrudging him nothing, all I
would do is to lovingly forgive him, for

02:04:48.540 --> 02:04:55.139
impermanent is my body of blood. Danger
and death are constant foes,

02:04:55.139 --> 02:05:00.320
